1. c3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. Nb3 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 2... a5 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 3. f4 { not just attacking to center, but here i have a very uncommon early tactical idea with light-squares: blacks piece arrangement looks bit awkward, so with f4, i make Qf3 possible with the following idea: } { [%csl Ge5,Gf4,Ga8,Gb7,Gc8,Gd8] [%clk 0:03:03] } 3... a4 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 4. Nc5 { provoking d6. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gd7d6] [%clk 0:03:04] } 4... d6 { [%clk 0:02:37] } 5. Nxb7 { [%cal Gc5b7,Gf1f3] [%clk 0:02:52] } 5... Nxb7 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 6. Qf3 { important was to be aware of that there is no Ra7 due to bishop on g1. i believe this is very uncommon pattern in such an early stage of game. White takes the full advantage of light squares. } { [%csl Gb7,Gc8,Ga8][%cal Gf3a8,Ga8a7,Gg1a7] [%clk 0:02:54] } 6... d5 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 7. Qxd5 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 7... Ncd6 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 8. fxe5 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 8... f6 { [%clk 0:02:24] } 9. Qc6+ { an important zwischenzug (in-between) check. } { [%clk 0:02:52] } 9... Kd8 { [%clk 0:02:20] } 10. exd6 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 10... Qxd6 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 11. Qxb7 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 11... Bd5 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 12. Qb5 { bg2 bc5 and rook comes out. } { [%csl Gh1][%cal Gd5g2,Gg1c5] [%clk 0:02:14] } 12... Bc6 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 13. Qh5 { important to keep the Queen on 5th rank for Bc5 } { [%csl Gg2,Gc5][%cal Gg7g6,Gh5h3] [%clk 0:02:01] } 13... Bxg2 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 14. Bc5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:01:59] } 1-0


