1. d4 { Notes by Geza Maroczy } 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be6 7. e4 { The right continuation was here : 7 Bxf6 Qxf6 8 e4 dxe4
9 Bb5+ Bd7 10 Nxe4 (better than 10 Bxd7+ Nxd7 11 Nxe4 on account of ...Qa6!)
followed by Bb5+ and O-O. } 7... Be7 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Ne5 { Here White could have
prevented his opponent from castling but it would not have been any more
advantageous, for instance : 9 Bxf6 Bxf6 10 exd5 Bxd5 11 Qe2+ Kf8, etc. } 9... Rc8 10. Qa4 cxd4 { Very well played! } 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. O-O Rfd8 16. Rfe1 c5 17. Nxd5 Rxd5 18. Qe3 { White could very
well fall into a very interesting trap. As it seems White wins the exchange
with Nc6, but in fact he loses the game : 18 Nc6 Qd7 19 Ne7+ Kf8! and black
wins. } 18... h6 19. h3 Qb7 20. b3 Rcd8 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


