1. d4 { Notes by Geza Maroczy } 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c4 e6 5. Be2 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 { First dxc5 is to be considered. } 7... b6 8. b3 Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Rc1 Qe7 { The king bishop is after the fianchetto development better
placed on d6 because the queen has obviously few places left.The opening turns
out favorably for Black. } 11. Nb5 Bb8 12. Ne5 a6 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. Nc3 Rd8 15. Bf3 Nf6 16. cxd5 { Na4 ought to have been played immediately, after the text
move it is a mistake. } 16... exd5 17. Na4 c4 18. bxc4 dxc4 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. g3 b5 { Black has got a considerable majority of pawns on the q-side. } 21. Nc5 Qc6 22. Qc2 Bd6 23. Nd3 Rac8 24. Ne5 { The black pawns grow thereby stronger. White
has no counterchance, his game is lost. } 24... Bxe5 25. dxe5 Ne4 26. Bd4 Ng5! 27. f3 Nxf3+ 28. Rxf3 Qxf3 29. Rf1 Qg4 30. Qf2 Qg6 31. Qb2 h6 32. Rf4 c3 33. Bxc3 Rd1+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


