1. d4 { Notes by Alekhine } 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 { The modern
defence which has not as yet found its refutation. } 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 { After 5 e3
Black can play 5...e5 at once (Keres vs. Alekhine, Dresden, 1936. } 5... d6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 a5 { The necessity for this move depends on the right solution
of the question whether Black can sacrifice a pawn by playing 8...e5; after
7...O-O 8 b4. In the game Fine vs. Van den Bosch (Amsterdam, 1936) Black after
9 dxe5 dxe5 10 Nxe5 Nxe5 11 Qxe5 Re8 12 Qb2 (Flohr's move introduced a new move
12...Qd3, which brought his opponent into difficulties. Although White finally
won the game the whole variation still deserves a closer examination. } 8. Bg5 { As the bishop can hardly avoid the exchange a more promising development
appears to be 8 g3 or even 8 b3. } 8... h6 9. Bxf6 { Very harmless. But after 9
Bh4 the pinning of the knight would be without much effect as Black would
always have the move. } 9... Qxf6 10. e3 O-O 11. Be2 e5 { Black has obviously not
the slightest difficulties. } 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. O-O Bg4 { This manoeuver is out
of place as Black's squares d7 and d5 are not sufficiently protected. But also
after the better move 13...Bf5 White would proceed to liquidate on the open
queen's file. } 14. h3 Bh5 15. Rfd1 Rfe8 { Otherwise White's next move would have
threatened Black's e-pawn. } 16. Rd5 Bg6 { Black admits that the bishop's
excursion was useless. } 17. Rad1 Bf5 18. R5d2 { If 18 Rb5 simply 18...Rab8 and
Black's position would remain safe. } 1/2-1/2


