[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "960 Starting positions and square control"]
[ChapterName "Standard 518"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5do3bfAh/Ba2Wph0U"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/1p2p3/6p1/8/RNBQKBNR w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.12.23"]
[UTCTime "09:00:50"]

{ I cut the board into half and look for uncontrolled squares. I place black pawns for these undefended points for visualization.

Aim of this study is to
1) look how different 960 starting positions differ from each other in terms of number of uncontrolled squares to begin with.
2) To see if there is a correlation between this number and piece harmony.
3) To see if the numbers mean anything for the potential in harmonious piece development, e.g. if higher the number, harder position to start and develop with? Etc.

So far, at least 3 squares remain undefended, at most 8 squares remain uncontrolled. } { [%cal Gb5h5,Gg5a5] }
 *


[Event "960 Starting positions and square control: Notes on 518."]
[Date "2020.12.23"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "960 Starting positions and square control"]
[ChapterName "Notes on 518."]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5do3bfAh/BPDu4Hgm"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/RNBQKBNR w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.12.23"]
[UTCTime "11:17:51"]

{ Why is our standard position said to be most harmonious and perfect starting position?

1) Symmetry. Except king and queen, which are one of a kind, all the pieces, who exist in pairs are placed symmetrical.

2) The set up order of RNBxxBNR leaves no undefended pawns on 2nd rank. If for example rook and knights were swapped, a2 and h2 would be weak point. So this means, this constellation of RNB is very efficient and uses maximum potential of minors.

3)Rooks placed in the corners allows other pieces to be more efficient (see chapter 27)

4)Queen in the middle controls 9 squares. Bishops 5+5=10. But 4 squares are double protected, so instead of 9+10=19, 15 unique squares.
Question: How would it be differ in bishop pair was in the middle? As 6+6=12 (2 more than c1-f1 set up) but queen moved to side (c1 or f1) or makes only 8 (one less than on d1) so 2-1=1 more in total. See chapter 29-31 } { [%csl Ga2,Ga3,Ga4,Gb3,Gb2,Gd4,Gd3,Gd2,Gc3,Gc2,Gc4,Ge3,Ge2,Gf4,Gf3,Gf2,Gg4,Gh4,Gh3,Gh2,Gg2][%cal Gb5h5,Gg5a5] }
 *


