1. g3 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 1... g6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 2. f4 { [%clk 0:04:51] } 2... f5 { [%clk 0:04:59] } 3. d4 { [%clk 0:04:46] } 3... Nb6 { [%clk 0:04:56] } 4. e4 { [%clk 0:04:38] } 4... Bc4 { [%clk 0:04:53] } (4... fxe4 5. Bxe4 Bc4 { was another way how to disrupt white's piece coordination. } 6. Rf3 d5 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. cxd3 { Black has a comfortable position and the whole game is ahead. }) 5. e5! { [%clk 0:04:31] } 5... Bxf1 { [%clk 0:04:52] } 6. Kxf1 { [%clk 0:04:31] } 6... d6 { [%clk 0:04:38] } 7. Nb3 { [%clk 0:04:21] } 7... dxe5 { [%clk 0:04:28] } 8. dxe5 { [%clk 0:04:18] } 8... Ne6 { [%clk 0:04:25] } 9. a4 { White intends to activate his queen and also prepares the a4-a5-a6 advance. } { [%clk 0:04:02] } 9... c6 { [%clk 0:03:59] } (9... Nxa4? 10. Qa2 Nb6 11. Na5) 10. Qa2 { [%clk 0:03:44] } 10... Qc7 { [%clk 0:03:58] } (10... Bxe5! { was the right way, activating the queen and starting attack against white's exposed king. In the game my bishop played a sad role on h8, staying inactive until the very end. } 11. a5! (11. fxe5? { [%csl Gf5] } 11... f4 { would have given black a winning attack. It is important that he can still castle to any side. }) 11... Nc4 $17 { was very strong } (11... Bxf4 12. axb6 Bxc1 13. bxa7 Qd6 14. Nf2 Ra8 15. Nxc1 f4 $17 { is a funny line which also favours black. })) 11. Ne3 { [%clk 0:03:39] } 11... g5 { [%clk 0:03:51] } (11... Bxe5! { was very strong even here. } 12. a5 (12. fxe5? f4 13. gxf4 Qxe5 { gives black a crushing attack, as white can no longer castle. }) 12... Nd7 13. a6 b6) 12. Bf3! { [%clk 0:03:22] } 12... O-O-O? { [%clk 0:03:31] } (12... g4! { I was reluctant to close the kingside, but black can still sacrifice the bishop on e5 if white's bishop retreats. }) 13. a5 { [%clk 0:03:10] } 13... Nd5 { [%clk 0:03:30] } 14. Nxd5 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 14... cxd5? { [%clk 0:03:30] } (14... Rxd5 { was a lesser evil, but far from impressive. } 15. Bxa7! (15. Bxd5 cxd5 16. Nd4 $16) 15... gxf4 16. Bb6 Qd7 17. a6 Kb8 18. Na5 { Black's king is unlikely to survive the assault. }) 15. c4! { [%clk 0:02:55] } 15... d4 { [%clk 0:03:25] } 16. a6 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 16... b6 { [%clk 0:03:20] } 17. c5! $18 { White opens the c-file for his rook as well as the diagonals for his queen. Black is already lost. } { [%clk 0:02:49] } 17... Kb8 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 18. cxb6 { [%clk 0:02:37] } (18. Na5! bxa5 19. Qb3+! $18) 18... Qxb6 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 19. Na5 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 19... Qxa6+ { [%clk 0:02:38] } (19... Rc8 20. Nc6+ Rxc6 21. Rxc6 Qb5+ { was more tenacious, but still bad after } 22. Kg2) 20. Kg2 { [%clk 0:02:25] } 20... Rc8 { [%clk 0:02:31] } 21. Rc6! { [%clk 0:02:08] } 21... Qb5 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 22. Qxe6 { [%clk 0:01:50] } 22... g4 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 23. Bd5 { [%clk 0:01:37] } (23. Rxc8+ Rxc8 24. Nc6+ Kb7 25. Qxc8+ Kxc8 26. Nxa7+ { was what I expected, but the text is also winning. }) 23... Qxa5 { [%clk 0:01:52] } (23... Rcd8! { was more tenacious. White maintains some advantage after the bishop retreats, but black could take on a5 and fight on. While } 24. Rc5!! Qxc5 25. Nc6+ Kc7 26. Nb4!! Rxd5 (26... Qxb4 27. Qc6+ Kb8 28. Qa8+ Kc7 29. Qxa7+ Kc8 30. Be6+ Rd7 31. Bxd7+ Kd8 32. Bc6 Kc8 33. Bxd4 Rd8 34. Bc3 Rd2+ 35. Kg1 Rd1+ 36. Kf2 $18 { is another complex computer line, but here white also has other paths. }) 27. Na6+! Kd8 28. Nxc5 Rxc5 29. Bxd4 { wins quickly due to black's weak king and complete lack of pieces coordination, I doubt that anyone would have found that line in blitz. }) 24. Bxd4 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 24... Rfd8 { Here white executed a nice final combination. } { [%clk 0:01:22] } 25. Bxa7+! { The only winning move! } { [%clk 0:00:49] } 25... Kxa7 { [%clk 0:01:22] } (25... Qxa7 26. Rb6+ Kc7 27. Qc6#) 26. Qxe7+ { [%clk 0:00:48] } 26... Kb8 { I had seen this while playing 24...Rfd8, but missed a "small detail" and only spotted it after my move. That said, black's position had been lost anyway. } { [%clk 0:01:21] } 27. Rxc8+ { [%clk 0:00:46] } 27... Kxc8 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 28. Qb7# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:00:46] } 1-0


