lace his rook on c1, bishop on d6 and enjoy a positional advantage. }) 15... Nf4+ { [%clk 0:00:21] } 16. Kf2 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 16... Bxg4 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 17. hxg4 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 17... a5! { Black activates his queen and intends to bring his rook into play. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 18. Ba3 { White still prevents castling. With my next move I intended to change that by pushing b6-b5-b4. } { [%clk 0:01:46] } 18... b5 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 19. Bc5 { [%clk 0:01:28] } (19. Qc5 b4 20. Bc1 Qa7 { is still better for black but less convincing. } (20... Qa6)) 19... d6 { [%clk 0:00:17] } (19... Qa6! $17 { was the best move, preparing d7-d6. }) 20. Bb6+ { [%clk 0:01:26] } 20... Kd7 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 21. Qc3! { I underestimated this move. } { [%clk 0:01:19] } (21. d5! { And this one I simply missed. Black remains better in theory, but in practice anything could happen. } 21... e5 $17 { is safe and good } (21... Qb7 22. dxe6+ Kxe6 23. Qe3 Rc8 { is even stronger, but less safe. })) 21... Rc8?! { [%clk 0:00:08] } (21... b4! 22. Qc4 Rc8 23. Qb5+ Ke7 24. Bxa5 Ba7! 25. Rd1 e5! $17 { was the best way, but I did not find it. }) 22. Qxa5 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 22... Qxa5 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 23. Bxa5 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 23... Ba7! { [%clk 0:00:12] } 24. Rd1 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 24... e5 { [%clk 0:00:13] } (24... Rh8 { is an engine recommendation, threatening h4-h3. The d4-pawn would not survive long anyway. But was really hard to find and appreciate, given that the rook looked good on c8. }) 25. g3?? { Blitz games are usually decided by blunders rather than through great ideas. We all make blunders, in the previous game with the same opponent it was me who made the last two. } { [%clk 0:01:05] } 25... Bxd4+ { [%clk 0:00:12] } 26. Rxd4 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 26... hxg3+ { I assume that white missed this intermediate move while playing 25.g3. } { [%clk 0:00:14] } 27. Kxg3 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 27... exd4 $19 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 28. e5 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 28... dxe5 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 29. Bf5+ { [%clk 0:00: