{ This was a tough game with many ups and downs, which also contained some remarkable tactics. }
1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. e4 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 2... dxe4 { [%clk 0:02:56] } 3. Qxe4 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 3... c5! { [%clk 0:02:32] } 4. c3 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 4... cxd4 { [%clk 0:02:24] } 5. cxd4 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 5... Nb6 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 6. Nb3 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 6... Be6 { [%clk 0:01:37] } (6... Nd5 7. Ne3 Nf6! { was good for black, who enjoys a better pawn structure. }) 7. Ne3 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 7... Nd5 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 8. O-O { [%clk 0:02:31] } 8... Qc6?! { Playing for tricks. It worked this time! } { [%clk 0:01:09] } 9. Nc5 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 9... Nxe3 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 10. Qxc6?! { Any recapture on e3 would have granted white an edge. } { [%clk 0:02:15] } (10. fxe3! Qxe4 11. Bxe4 b6 12. Nxe6 Nxe6 13. Bd2 $14 { and white has an edge due to the bishop pair. }) 10... Bxh2+! { [%clk 0:01:12] } 11. Kh1! { [%clk 0:02:05] } (11. Kxh2? Nxf1+ 12. Rxf1 bxc6 $19) 11... bxc6 { [%clk 0:01:13] } 12. Nxe6 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 12... Nxe6 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 13. fxe3 { [%clk 0:02:00] } (13. Bxe3 Bc7 14. Be4 Bb6 $15) 13... Bd6 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 14. e4 { [%clk 0:01:58] } 14... O-O { [%clk 0:00:56] } 15. Be3 { [%clk 0:01:58] } 15... c5 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 16. e5? { This looks tempting, but white has fallen into my trap. } { [%clk 0:01:38] } (16. d5! Nc7?! (16... Nd4! 17. b4! e5! 18. dxe6 Nxe6 19. b5! $44 { and white's queenside pawn majority combined with a bishop pair would give him reasonable counterchances. }) 17. Rc1! $14 { I somehow did not notice that I would lose the pawn back. }) 16... cxd4! { [%clk 0:00:32] } 17. exd6 { [%clk 0:01:39] } 17... dxe3 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 18. dxe7 { A fork! } { [%clk 0:01:40] } 18... e2 { A counterfork! :-) No wonder that I went for a dinner after this game! } { [%clk 0:00:36] } 19. exf8=R+ { [%clk 0:01:08] } 19... Nxf8! { This is a bit more accurate than 19...Rxf8, which was also good. } { [%clk 0:00:38] } 20. Rde1 { [%clk 0:01:04] } (20. Bc2 Rd2! { is really nice, but I would have played something prosaic instead, possibly 20...Rxd1 with a transition into a winning minor piece endgame. }) 20... exf1=Q+ { [%clk 0:00:39] } 21. Rxf1 { [%clk 0:01:06] } 21... Rd2 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 22. b3 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 22... g6 { Black is technically winning, but also tired and a bit short of time. The rest of the game was not really nice, so feel free to skip it. The most interesting parts have passed. } { [%clk 0:00:27] } 23. Kh2 { [%clk 0:01:06] } 23... Ne6 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 24. Rc1 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 24... Kg7 { [%clk 0:00:23] } 25. a3 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 25... Rb2 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 26. Bc2 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 26... Nd4 { [%clk 0:00:10] } (26... Nf4! { , threatening 27...Ne2, was winning a second pawn and the game. }) 27. Bd1 { [%clk 0:00:52] } 27... Nxb3 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 28. Rc7 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 28... Nd4 { [%clk 0:00:08] } (28... a5 29. Rb7 a4 30. Rb4 Rd2 31. Bxb3 axb3 32. Rxb3 Ra2 { is still an easy technical win, but I was too short of time to realize that. }) 29. Rxa7 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 29... Rd2 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 30. Bg4 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 30... h5 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 31. Bc8 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 31... Nb5 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 32. Ra5 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 32... Nd6 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 33. Ba6 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 33... Ra2 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 34. a4 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 34... Ra3 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 35. Be2 { [%clk 0:00:35] } 35... Nf5? { [%clk 0:00:06] } 36. Bxh5! { [%clk 0:00:29] } 36... Ne3 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 37. Bf3 $10 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 37... f5 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 38. Ra7+ { [%clk 0:00:26] } 38... Kf6 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 39. a5 { [%clk 0:00:28] } (39. Ra6+! $10) 39... g5 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 40. a6? { [%clk 0:00:22] } (40. Ra8! g4 41. Bb7 f4 42. Rf8+ Ke5 43. Re8+ Kd6 44. Rf8 Nf1+ 45. Kg1 Ng3 46. Kf2 { still maintains equality. It is not the only way, but white's task has become difficult after 39.a5. }) 40... g4! { [%clk 0:00:09] } 41. Bc6 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 41... f4 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 42. g3 { [%clk 0:00:09] } (42. Ra8 g3+ { leads to a mate, but I was more focused on a knight transfer Ne3-f1-g3 with a subsequent mate on f1 or h1. It is less convincing if white defends well. } 43. Kh3 Ra1 44. Rf8+ Kg5 45. Rg8+ Kh6) 42... f3 { Black had quicker ways in the rest of the game, but I was low on time. } { [%clk 0:00:06] } 43. Be8 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 43... Ra2+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } 44. Kh1 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 44... f2 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 45. Rf7+ { [%clk 0:00:08] } 45... Ke6 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 46. Rxf2 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 46... Rxf2 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 47. a7 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 47... Ra2 { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%clk 0:00:10] } 0-1


