{ This was a game of Daily Chess (correspondence chess without computers). The game is a sort of curiosity, which shows that it is necessary to pay attention since the very beginning in Chess960. }
1. Ng3 g6 2. e4 { I was reluctant to
allow f7-f5. Now black's cornered knight looks strange, but white's pieces are
a bit clumsy as well. } 2... Bg7 3. c3 { White restricts the mobility of black's
bishop. } (3. Nc3!?) 3... d6 (3... b5 4. d4) (3... h5!? 4. h4 $14 (4. f3 h4 5. Nh1 $13 { . })) 4. Ne3 e5 (4... e6 5. a4! { the knight on e3 looks clumsy, but black cannot exploit it. } 5... f5?! 6. exf5 exf5 (6... gxf5 7. Nh5) 7. Nd5) (4... b5 { with } 5. a4 { , when } 5... b4 { allows } 6. Nd5 { . But it is not the most dangerous fork which
can occur. }) (4... O-O?? { loses for the same reason as in
the game. }) 5. a4 O-O?? 6. Nd5! { Black resigned, as he is unable to parry
both threats 7.Ne7# and 7.Nxc7 (winning the queen) at the same time! This game
is not a brilliancy, but its finale is highly unusual and easy to miss. } 1-0


