{ This is a game from chess.com. Some players like me were lucky enough to get "normal" ratings before entering arenas, while others (like the opponent, an American FIDE master) were not and could only play other underrated opponents. (The online Chess960 ratings are irrelevant, I just want to explain that the real difference in strength was several hundred points lower
than the numbers indicate.) }
1. f4 f5 2. Ng3 c6 3. Bd4 { At first I became worried about the g7-pawn, but
then I noticed that it was protected by the knight. } 3... Ng6 4. e3 d6! { Black
would like to push e7-e5. } 5. Nf3 (5. Qh5!? { the } 5... e5 { advance is less
convincing, e.g. } 6. fxe5 dxe5 7. Bc5 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Nxd6 9. Nxf5 Kc7! $36 { . While the pin along the f-file gives black nice compensation, it would not
be easy to find that line, assess it properly and continue accurately. }) 5... e5 6. fxe5 dxe5 7. Bc3 Qd7 8. Qe2 e4 9. Nd4 Nd6? (9... Bxg3! 10. hxg3 Ne5! $17 { would have stabilised the centre, preparing queenside castling and
generating a threat of 11...c5, 12...Bc4 at the same time. }) 10. Qh5? (10. Bb4! $13) 10... Ne7 11. b3 c5 12. Nde2 Nd5 13. Bb2 Bc7 14. Nc3 O-O-O 15. Nxd5 g6! (15... Bxd5 16. Qxh7 { was also very good for black with various
tactical motifs in the air, I decided to avoid such complications. }) 16. Qh4 Bxd5 $19 17. c4?! (17. O-O { white's position would only be
strategically bad with the passive queenside. But now black starts a decisive
attack. }) 17... Bxc4! (17... Nxc4 18. bxc4 Bxc4 19. Rd1 Ba5! $19 { . }) 18. bxc4 Nxc4 19. Bc3 Nxd2 (19... Be5? 20. O-O! Bxc3 21. dxc3 Nxe3 $17) 20. Rd1?! (20. Re1 { black can win in many ways, e.g. } 20... Be5!? 21. Bxe5 Nf3! (21... Nb3+?! { , when } 22. Kb2! Qd2+? 23. Bc2! $13 { is no longer great for black. }) 22. gxf3 Qd2#) (20. Rf2! Nc4! 21. Bc2 $19 { , although it
is also lost. White's major pieces are doing little to protect the monarch. A
funny detail - white can still unexpectedly castle to the queenside, moving
his rook to d1! }) 20... Nb3+ 21. axb3 Qxd1+ 22. Kb2 Rd2+! 23. Bxd2 Qxd2+ 24. Bc2 Be5+ { FormerProdigy won on time } 0-1


