[ChapterName "Emanuel Lasker - Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/KwqXytfb/aqJ2IUV6"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nge7 (5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Be7 7. Be3 Nf6 { So we can conclude that knight belongs to f6 and not to g6 like in the game. From f6, he counters the Nd5. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gf6d5,Gc3d5] }) 6. Be3 Ng6 { problem in this line is apparently d5 square. additionally, black has to solve dark square bishop issue. } { [%csl Gd5,Gf8] } 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O a6 9. Be2 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 { Now white controls center. Knight on g6 is really misplaced, because in an opposite-castle game, it is all about a race. Knight on g6 allows white to push his pawns much more quickly. } { [%csl Gd5,Gg7][%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] } 11... Bf6 12. Qd2 { Even b5 cannot help now as black cannot launch an attack easily, as he cannot transfer pieces to queenside (for example c5-Qa5 is not possible to due d6). And if you cannot bring your queen, how can you attack. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] } 12... Bc6 (12... b5) 13. Nd5 { White seizes the center. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4] } 13... O-O { [%cal Gh2h4] } 14. g4 (14. h4 { h4 is even faster. } { [%cal Gh4h5] }) 14... Re8 15. g5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5? { Allows rook e5 with tempo also the point of exd5 was to open the d3-h3 diagonal for bishop } { [%csl Ge5,Ge2][%cal Ge8e5] } (16. exd5 Be5 (16... Rxe3 17. fxe3 Bxg5 { Only chance for black. }) 17. Bd3 { easy attack. } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] }) 16... Re5 17. Qd2 Bxg5 18. f4 Rxe4 19. fxg5 Qe7 20. Rdf1 Rxe3 21. Bc4 { [%csl Gf7] } 21... Nh8? { knight does not belong to h8. } (21... Rf8) 22. h4 c6 23. g6!? { a practical move that creates a pressure on king. } 23... d5 { A move played with logic of fear. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } (23... hxg6 24. h5 gxh5 25. Rxh5 { It might be holdable with precise defense, but it is practically hard. } { [%csl Gg8,Gh8] }) 24. gxh7+ Kxh7 25. Bd3+ Kg8 26. h5 { [%csl Gh8][%cal Gf1g1] } 26... Re8 27. h6 g6 { [%csl Gh8] } 28. h7+ Kg7 29. Kb1 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gd2h2,Gh2h6] } 29... Qe5 30. a3 c5 31. Qf2 c4 32. Qh4 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gh4h6] } 32... f6 33. Bf5! { he must have seen this couple moves ago. } 33... Kf7 34. Rhg1 gxf5 35. Qh5+ Ke7 36. Rg8 Kd6 37. Rxf5 Qe6 (37... Re1+ 38. Ka2 Qe2 { [%csl Gb1,Gb3][%cal Ge2d1,Gd1b1] } 39. Rxd5+ { this is psychologically hard to allow. Black forces white to exchange queens with mating threat on b1. } { [%csl Gc2,Gc4,Gb1][%cal Ge2c2,Ge2d1] } 39... Kc6 40. Rc5+ Kb6 41. Qf5 Qd1 (41... Qe4 { [%csl Gc2,Gc5][%cal Gf5e4,Gf5c5,Gb6c5] } 42. Qh5 Qxc2 { [%csl Gb1,Gb3] })) 38. Rxe8 Qxe8 39. Rxf6+ Kc5 40. Qh6 Re7 41. Qh2 Qd7 42. Qg1+ d4 43. Qg5+ Qd5 44. Rf5 Qxf5 45. Qxf5+ Kd6 46. Qf6+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Summary of the game: White had an advantage in the opening due to control of d5 square, allowed by the misplaced knight on g6. But he failed to create an effective attack. (h4 instead of g4 and Qxd5) Qxd5 instead of exd5 has allowed black into the game. White has kept putting psychological pressure, which eventually lead tactical failure by black. } 1-0


