1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Ng3 c5 7. Be2 cxd4 8. Nxd4 { Lets make a pause and look at pawn structure. White has a 3-2 on qside and black has 4-3 majority in kside. What does that mean and how does this influence or determine game plan of both sides? } { [%csl Gc2,Gb2,Ga2,Gb7,Ga7,Ge6,Gf7,Gg7,Gh7,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2] } 8... Bc5 9. Nb3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bd2 Qc7 12. c4 Ne5 13. Qc2 Ng6 14. Rfe1 Bd7 15. Rac1 Rfc8 16. Bf1 Ba4 17. Bc3 Ng4 18. Qe2 Nf6 { Black has wasted tempo with Ng4-f6. } 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. b4 Rd8 21. Qb2 Rac8 22. Nb3 Qf4 { Just like Ng4, this move also does not have a valid point. } 23. Bd2 Qb8 24. b5 b6 25. Bc3 Ne8 { If we compare current position with position after 8th move, we can see that pawn structure on kingside has not changed a bit, while white has made a progress (expended) on queenside. Apart from the structural change, both sides we re regrouping his pieces over the last 17 moves. } 26. Nh5? { Nh5 achieves nothing for white. White apparently wants to provoke f6. But this actually helps black to improve his position slowly. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf7f6,Ge6e5] } (26. Ne4 { White should instead have focused on continuing his plan on queenside. By bringing knight to e5 rather than h5. So this a conceptual issue. } { [%csl Ge4,Gh5][%cal Ga2a4,Gc4c5,Gg3e4] }) 26... f6 27. a4 e5 { black can play e5-f6 without much concern as c4 pawn blocks Bc4. Also now bishop on d7 has some mobility } { [%csl Gf1,Gc4,Gd7] } 28. a5 { [%csl Ge6,Gf5,Gg4,Gd7] } 28... Bg4 29. Ng3 Be6 30. Nd2 Nf4 31. Qb1 { Now compare this position to 6 moves ago. Without any deep looking, one can visually see it easily that black clearly made some progress and whites pieces kept going backwards. Something must have been gone wrong. If we trace it back, we would come back to Nh5. } { [%csl Gb1,Gd2,Gg3][%cal Gh5g3,Gb3d2,Gb2b1] } 31... Bf7 32. Nf5 Bf8 33. Bb4 Nd6 34. Nxd6 { [%csl Gd4] } 34... Bxd6 35. Ne4 Bxb4 36. Qxb4 { Even though it might be equal, it is now easier to play with black. } { [%csl Gd4,Gd3,Gc8,Gd8,Gc4][%cal Gc8c4] } 36... Rd4 { After the series of exchanges on d6, white was deprived of any minor pieces that could control d4. } 37. axb6 axb6 38. g3 { This just weakens kingside. } { [%csl Gg2,Gf3,Gh3,Gc5][%cal Gf4e6,Ge6c5] } 38... Nd3 39. Bxd3 Rxd3 40. c5 { Now it is quite hard to play with white, as light square weakness on kingside looks dangerous. White will now be forced to constantly keep checking possible threats on light squares. In a practical game, such situations usually lead to a mistake due to using too much energy on considering possible threats. This could be an explanation of the blunder on move 43. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge4,Gg2,Gh3,Gf3] } 40... Rd4 41. Qb1 bxc5 42. Nxc5 Rc4 43. Nd7? { [%csl Gd7] } 43... Qb7 44. Rcd1?? Be6 { Knight is trapped. } { [%csl Gd7] } 45. Nxe5 fxe5 46. Rxe5 Bh3 { [%csl Gg2,Gf3] } 47. Red5 Rc1 48. Qd3 (48. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 49. Qxc1 Qxd5 { [%csl Gg2,Gc8][%cal Gd5g2,Gc1c8,Gh3c8] }) 48... h6 49. g4 Bxg4 50. f3 Rxd1+ 51. Qxd1 Be6 52. Rd6 Qe7 53. b6 Rc1 54. Qxc1 Qxd6 55. Qe3 Bd5 56. Kg2 Qg6+ 57. Kf2 Qc2+ 58. Kg3 Qg6+ 59. Kf2 Qc2+ 60. Kg3 Qg6+ 61. Kf2 { Back in the days, there was no threefold repetition. } 61... Bb7 62. Qb3+ Qf7 63. Qd3 Qd5 64. Qe3 Qd6 65. Kg2 Kf7 66. h4 Qe6 67. Qf4+ Kg6 68. Qg3+ Kh7 69. Qf2 Qg4+ 70. Kh2 Qxf3 71. Qc2+ Qe4 72. Qf2 Qf3 73. Qc2+ Be4 74. Qd2 Qf6 75. Qe3 Qxh4+ 76. Kg1 Qg5+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


