1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Nc3 a6 5. Bc4 { Deviates from book. } 5... Be6 6. Bxe6 fxe6 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Ne7 10. Bg5 Nc6 11. Bxd8? { This exchange was also unnecessary for white. A simple retreat to Qd2 would be better, keeping more pieces on the board. } (11. Qd2) 11... Nxd4 12. O-O-O Nb5? (12... Rxd8 13. Rxd4 { black would have much better chances in this ending with bishop against knigh, as knight does not have a good square to go. One idea for black would be: } { [%csl Gf8,Gc3] } 13... g6 { [%cal Gf8g7] } 14. Rd3 Bg7 { force white to play f3. put bishop on e5 and go for a minority attack. } { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg7e5,Gg6g5,Gh7h5,Ge8e7,Gd8f8] }) 13. Nxb5 axb5 14. Bxc7 Rxa2 { Black has unnecessarily ruined his pawn structure by entering line with 12...Nb5. } { [%csl Gb5,Gb7,Gd6,Ge6,Gg7,Gh7] } 15. Bb6 Be7 16. c3 { [%cal Gc1c2,Gc2b3,Gb3b4] } 16... Kf7 17. Kc2 Rha8 18. Kb3 R2a4 19. f3 { [%csl Ge4,Gf3,Gg2,Ge7] } 19... R8a6 20. Bd4 g6 { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] } 21. Rd3 Ke8 22. Rhd1 e5? { by putting pawns on dark squares, black not only limits his bishops activity, but also give white targets. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd6] } 23. Be3 { Black has voluntarily fixed his pawns on dark squares and created weaknesses. } { [%csl Gd6,Ge5,Ge3] } 23... Kd7 { [%csl Gd5] } 24. Bc5 Ra1 25. R1d2 Ke6 26. Ba3 { [%csl Gd5] } 26... g5 { [%csl Gd5] } 27. Rd5 Rb6 28. Kb4 { [%cal Gb4a5] } 28... g4 29. Ka5 Ra6+ 30. Kxb5 { Black should at least try to harass pawns and not let Rd1. } { [%cal Ga1h1] } 30... h5 31. Rd1! { not giving any counter-chances. } 31... Rxd1 32. Rxd1 gxf3 33. gxf3 Ra8 34. Kb6 Rg8 35. Kxb7 Rg2 36. h4 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ge7h4,Gd1h1,Gd1d6] } 36... Rh2 (36... Bxh4 37. Rh1 (37. Rxd6+) 37... Bf6 38. Rxh5) 37. Kc6 { [%csl Gd6] } 37... Bxh4 38. Rxd6+ Kf7 39. Kd5 Bf6 40. Rd7+ Kg6 41. Ke6 h4 42. Rd1 h3 43. Rg1+ Rg2 44. Rxg2+ hxg2 45. Bc5 Bd8 46. b4 Kg5 47. Kd7 Bf6 48. b5 Kf4 49. b6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Black has simply put himself in a difficult pawn structure through an unfavourable series of exchanges. He then helped white by fixing his pawns on d6-e5. In return, black was not able to create counter chances. (Rd1!) White slowly collected isolated pawns and won. } 1-0


