1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3?! { White is being experimental. Having a center with f3-e4 looks appealing, but it is too good to be true. Whenever f pawn moves, black typically counters it with c5 and open g1-c5 diagonal to exploit dark square weaknesses. } 4... c5! 5. dxc5 Bxc5 { [%csl Gf2,Ge3,Gd4,Ge1] } 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. e4 Nxc3 (7... Qh4+ 8. g3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qf6 { Black could keep queens on the board while white will have hard time with finding shelter for his king. } { [%csl Ge1,Ge3,Gf2,Gc5] }) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. bxc3 Nc6 10. Nh3 Kc7 { Question is, how to coordinate Whites pieces? } { [%csl Gh3,Gf1,Gc1,Ga1,Gh1] } 11. Nf4 Rd8 12. Nd3 { Knight certainly does not belong to d3. Manoeuvering knight to d3 was the first step in the wrong direction of strategy. } { [%csl Gf1,Gc1,Gd3] } 12... Bd6 13. f4 { 2nd wrong step. f4 does not improve whites position a bit but on the contrary. Both bishops are blocked, without developing bishops, rooks wont be connected and knight is misplaced on d3. White is having hard time to coordinate his pieces. Main problem is: Whites pieces lack communication. } { [%csl Gd3,Gf4][%cal Gf1d3,Gc1f4] } 13... b6 14. Nf2 Bc5 15. Be2 Bb7 16. Nd3 Bf8 17. f5 e5 18. Bg5 f6 19. Be3 { 3rd step in the wrong direction. f5-Bg5. This pawn structure apparently favours black as e4 is a target and whites bishops are not in harmony with pawn structure. } { [%csl Gf5,Ge4,Gc3] } 19... Rac8 20. O-O-O Kb8 { Black has a clear plan: hit e4, hit c3. } { [%csl Gc3,Gc1,Gc8][%cal Gb7e4] } 21. Nf2 { [%csl Ge4] } 21... Nd4! { Double attack which wins material by force. } { [%csl Gc3,Ge2][%cal Gc8c3] } 22. Bxd4 exd4 23. Bd3 (23. c4 b5 { not better. } { [%cal Gb5c4] }) 23... dxc3 24. g4 { Knight could not find a good place in the whole game. But this is now not the biggest issue of white.. } { [%csl Ge4,Gf5,Gg4,Gd3,Gb7,Gf2] } 24... Ba3+ 25. Kc2 Bc6 { [%cal Gc6a4] } 26. Kb3 Bc5 { Bishop pair is too powerful to deal with. It is technically game over for white. } 27. Nh3 { [%cal Gh3f4,Gf4e6] } 27... Be3 { [%csl Gf4,Gf2][%cal Gd8d4,Gd4e4] } 28. Bc2 Bd2 29. Nf2 Rd4 30. Ka3 Be8 31. Nd3 Rxe4 32. Nb4 Rd4 33. Bb3 a5 34. Nc2 b5 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


