[Event "Import"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/WMFTvEbQ"]
[Date "1866"]
[White "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Black "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Result "0-1"]
[TimeControl "-"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Annotator "Tasshaq"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation, Anderssen Variation"]
[StudyName "Steinitz Classics"]
[ChapterName "Adolf Anderssen  - Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/50fv2T4h/lCtqsg3Q"]

{ This is a game that shows how Steinitz was ahead of his time and his deep positional vision. Even though it starts as a Berlin Defence, soon it transposes into a pawn structure that is typical for a Kings-Indian. Steinitz in this game successfully applies typical King-Indian plans in such a modern fashion, way before its theory has developed in detail. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. Bxc6+ { unprovoked exchange, which was not necessary. } 5... bxc6 6. h3 { White has given up a bishop but he is too slow to compensate for it with h3. Better would be simple 0-0 Re1 d4. } 6... g6 { Bishop is better on g7 than on e7 as he is more active on g7. } { [%cal Gf8g7,Gf8e7] } 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Be3 c5 { Controls d4 and now allowing white to play d4 and open the center. } { [%csl Gd4] } 11. Rb1 Ne8 { Amazing understanding of the needs of the position. Black first closed the center, now he is preparing to execute typical Kings-Indian attack on Kingside. Impressive is that Steinitz uses this plan in 1866! } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gf7f5] } 12. b4 cxb4 13. Rxb4 c5 14. Ra4 { Rook looks clumsy there, simple retreat would be better. This shows the typical understanding of that romantic era, where they cared less about positional factors, rather seeking active and attacking play in every opportunity. } { [%csl Gd4,Ga4] } 14... Bd7 15. Ra3 f5 { [%cal Gf5f4] } 16. Qb1 Kh8 { [%csl Gb3,Gg8][%cal Gb1b3] } 17. Qb7 a5 18. Rb1 a4 { ties whites rook there. This powerful bishop on d7 is both protecting a4 and keeping the attacking opportunities on h3 at the same time. } { [%csl Ga4,Gd7,Gb3,Ga3][%cal Gd7a4,Gd7h3] } 19. Qd5 Qc8 20. Rb6 Ra7 { rook on 7th rank. } { [%cal Ga7h7] } 21. Kh2 f4 22. Bd2 g5 { [%cal Gh6h5,Gg5g4] } 23. Qc4 Qd8 { [%csl Gg5,Gb6][%cal Gh6h5,Gg5g4,Gd8h4] } 24. Rb1 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6h7,Gh6h5,Gg5g4] } 25. Kg1 Nh7 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gh6h5,Gg5g4] } 26. Kf1 h5 27. Ng1 g4 28. hxg4 hxg4 29. f3 Qh4 { [%csl Gh4] } 30. Nd1 Ng5 { Beautiful knight play by Steinitz. Ne8 and Nh7 retreats and typical Ng5. } { [%csl Ge8,Gh7,Gg5] } 31. Be1 Qh2 32. d4 gxf3 33. gxf3 Nh3 34. Bf2 Nxg1 35. dxc5 Qh3+ 36. Ke1 Nxf3+ 37. Rxf3 Qxf3 38. Nc3 dxc5 39. Bxc5 Rc7 40. Nd5 Rxc5 41. Qxc5 Qxe4+ 42. Kf2 Rc8 43. Nc7 Qe3+ { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc5e3,Gf4e3,Gc8c7] } 0-1


[Event "Baltimore"]
[Site "Baltimore, MD USA"]
[Date "1885.02.09"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Black "Alexander G Sellman"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C11"]
[Opening "French Defense: Classical Variation, Steinitz Variation"]
[StudyName "Steinitz Classics"]
[ChapterName "Wilhelm Steinitz - Alexander G Sellman"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/50fv2T4h/Bdmn2CmA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 { Steinitz plays Steinitz variation. } 4... Nfd7 5. f4 { This is his idea. Before typically white playes Nce2 to reply c3 against c5. } { [%csl Gf4] } 5... c5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nf3 { At first it looks dangerous but white has a concrete idea in mind. } { [%cal Gc5g1] } 7... a6 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Qe2 Nb4 { Another waste of tempo after a6. As the exchange on d3 does not favour black and he spent 2 moves for it! } { [%csl Gb4,Gd3] } 10. Bd2 b5 11. Nd1 Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 { [%csl Ge4] } (12. Qxd3 { Capturing with queen does not improve position of the queen, but capturing with pawn improves pawn. Queen on d3 does not do a good job of controlling e4 as a pawn on d3 could do. After Qxd3, Blacks plan could be Bb6-Nc5-Bb7-Ne4. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge4][%cal Gc5b6,Gd7c5,Gc5e4,Gc8b7] }) 12... Qb6 { Strategical battle revolves around the fight of d4 square. } { [%csl Gd4] } 13. b4! { So, white kicks one piece away, that controls d4. } { [%csl Gb4,Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gb2b4] } 13... Be7 14. a3 { Whites is opting for a control on dark squares. } 14... f5 { And this only helps white. } 15. Rc1 Bb7 { This sad light square bishop gives away why Steinitz was insisting on controlling dark squares and fixing all blacks pawns on light squares. It shows Steinitzs deep understanding of the problem of bad bishop in french. } { [%csl Gb7] } 16. Be3 { [%csl Gd4] } 16... Qd8 17. Nd4 { Now that white finally took control of d4, it starts to create problems for black that are soon impossible to deal with. } { [%csl Ge6] } 17... Nf8 18. O-O h5 { Now Steinitz simply wants to improve position of the worst piece. Asks, where would the d1-knight ideally be placed? } { [%csl Gd1,Ga5] } 19. Nc3 Kf7 20. Nb1 g6 21. Nd2 Nd7 22. N2b3 Rc8 23. Na5 { And he answers in 4 moves: on a5! } { [%csl Ga5] } 23... Ba8 { [%csl Ga8] } 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 25. Rc1 Qb8 26. Qc2 { Control of the only open file. } { [%csl Gc7,Gc8] } 26... Bd8 27. Nac6 { White might look like offering a knight for the bad bishop, but he has a concrete point: transformation of positional advantage into a material one. After Bxc6 Qxc6, queen attacks a6,e6 and knight simultaneously. } { [%csl Gb8,Gd8] } 27... Qb7 (27... Bxc6 28. Qxc6 { [%csl Gd7,Ge6,Ga6] }) 28. Nxd8+ Rxd8 { They say: It is not important what you exchange, it is important what is left on the board! Here white is left with an unopposed dark square bishop against a tourist on a8. } { [%csl Ge3,Ga8] } 29. Qc7 Qb8 30. Bf2 { [%csl Gg5,Gf6,Ge7][%cal Gf2h4] } 30... Qb6 31. Nf3 { [%csl Gg5,Ge6,Gb6] } 31... Qxc7 32. Rxc7 Ke8 33. Ng5 Nf8 34. Bc5 { [%csl Ge7] } 34... Nd7 35. Bd6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Black collapses. What a smooth positional play by Steinitz and a skillful demonstration of the concept of exploiting a bad bishop in french! } { [%csl Ge6] } 1-0


