1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 exf4 4. d4 Qh4+ 5. Ke2 { [%csl Ge2] } 5... d6 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Bxf4 O-O-O 8. Ke3 { King is a strong piece, not only in the endgame but also in the middle game apparently! } { [%csl Ge3] } 8... Qh5 9. Be2 Qa5 { what is queen doing there? It would be more principled to try to open the center while king is in the middle. With f5 or even g5. } { [%csl Ga5] } (9... f5 { [%csl Gf5] }) (9... g5 { [%csl Gg5] }) 10. a3 { threatening b4 Qb6 Nd5 trapping the queen. } { [%csl Gd5,Ga5][%cal Gb2b4,Gc3d5] } 10... Bxf3 11. Kxf3 { Bishop pair. } { [%csl Ge2,Gf4] } 11... Qh5+ 12. Ke3 Qh4 { Queen has wasted a tempo, while white still controls the center and develop his pieces. } { [%cal Gh5a5,Gh5h4] } 13. b4 g5 14. Bg3 Qh6 15. b5 Nce7 16. Rf1 Nf6 { [%csl Gg1][%cal Ge3g1] } 17. Kf2 Ng6 18. Kg1 { as if he is castled. Now if we compare development of both sides, clearly white is ahead. With opposite side castles, it ll be a race, where white has an edge already with advanced b5 pawn. On the otherhand, queen on h6 is so misplaced that it hinders blacks attack and pawn advancement. } { [%csl Gf1,Gg1,Gh6,Gh7][%cal Gb5b6,Ga3a4,Ga4a5] } 18... Qg7 19. Qd2 h6 20. a4 Rg8 21. b6 { Every tempo counts! } 21... axb6 22. Rxf6!! { Very principled move by Steinitz. He wants to cut the communication between queen and queenside. } 22... Qxf6 23. Bg4+ Kb8 24. Nd5 { [%csl Ge6,Ge7,Gf5] } 24... Qg7 25. a5 f5 26. axb6 cxb6 (26... fxg4 27. bxc7+ { [%csl Gd8] }) 27. Nxb6 Ne7 (27... fxg4 28. Qc3 { mate next. } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Ga1a8] }) 28. exf5 Qf7 29. f6 Nc6 30. c4 Na7 31. Qa2 Nb5 32. Nd5 Qxd5 33. cxd5 Nxd4 34. Qa7+ Kc7 35. Rc1+ Nc6 36. Rxc6# { 1-0 Black resigns } 1-0


