[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/KEM1QMop/qGHjro5E"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]
[FEN "k6k/8/8/3pp3/3PP3/8/8/K6K w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.25"]
[UTCTime "11:55:35"]

{ Here in this endgame study series, i ll be selecting and presenting endgame positions which are either instructive or contain patterns that reveal geometrical insight that can deepen your understanding of fundamental basics, or simply positions that are theoretical wins&draws but which still require a demonstration of certain technique to achive the desired result.

These positions are usually extracted from real standard games and in most or at least some cases i ll be creating two parts of one game:

1. Part will be abstraction of the idea, which should be reached after some play of the initial position, which has either happened or could have happened in the real game.

2. Part will be the initial position that actually arose in the game and require some technique or play to reach that position where you can apply the idea from the first part. So basically these positions in the 2. part are meant for practice, which you can train by playing against computer over and over or against your friend, coach etc. which the idea from the first position in your mind and to get there.

This may sound all abstract now, but once you see the next two chapters, you will get a concrete idea of what i mean.

To sum up, 1. Parts are the abstract idea that you want to learn and keep in mind while playing the position presented in 2. Part. Of course, there might be more than one ways to win the initial position.

Sometimes there will be only 1.Part, the final idea, sometimes both. I wont be presenting those chapters in an systematical order such as first pawn endings than rook endings etc. but rather i ll add those positions whenever i encounter some position, in which i find some kind of instructive value.

I hope you will be able to find in them as much as value as i do.
Enjoy and always feel free to give some feedback!

Cheers! }
 *


[Event "Instructive Endgames: Position 1.1"]
[Date "2019.03.25"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Instructive Endgames"]
[ChapterName "Position 1.1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/KEM1QMop/A4eDog9g"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Tasshaq"]
[FEN "8/1KP1q3/8/8/8/8/3Q4/7k w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.25"]
[UTCTime "12:29:11"]

{ The problem white had here is that whenever King is on 7th rank, Black queen pins the pawn play staying on the 7th rank. If king goes b8, black puts his queen on h2-b8 diagonal. And Ka8 allows usually checks from a-file and then queen back to either 7th rank or h2-b8 diagonal.

So in order to promote c pawn, white needs to get out of the blacks pinning ideas. The question is how and what kind of set up needs white for that? }
1. Qh6+! Kg2 2. Qg6+ { and after King somewhere e.g. } 2... Kf1 3. Kc6!! { Now there are no more checks for black and no more pins! } { [%csl Ge6,Ge8,Ge4,Gc5,Gd7][%cal Gg6e8,Gg6e4,Gg6e6,Gc6c5,Gc6d7] } 3... Qf8 4. Kd7 { and white promotes in the next move. } { [%csl Gf7,Gg7,Ge8,Gf5,Gd6,Ge7][%cal Gc7c8,Gg6e8,Gg6f5,Gg6g7,Gd7e7,Gd7d6,Gd7e8] } *


