{ from the game https://lichess.org/WVarD4u4/black }
 *


[Event "Casual Rapid game"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/lOK7gESf"]
[Date "2020.06.08"]
[Round "-"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Jeffery Xiong"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2881"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackElo "2730"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[TimeControl "600+5"]
[Termination "Normal"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/STL_Admin"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Delayed Alapin Variation, with e6"]
[StudyName "Inspirational Games & Positional Masterpieces"]
[ChapterName "Magnus Carlsen - Jeffery Xiong"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/ws2N4krc/lG2TNh4O"]

1. e4 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 1... c5 { Opening theory is not my strength. Therefore i try to approach to positions the way i approach in 960. Which sometimes means, re-thinking about the opening moves that are played automatically. With other words, thinking about the simplest things and basic principles. Because i noticed this way of thinking, lets me dive into the game from the very early on and story of the game as a whole makes much more sense when everything once put together. } { [%csl Gd4,Gd5][%cal Ge4d5,Gc5d4] [%clk 0:10:00] } 2. Nf3 { Fighting for center. aiming for d4. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4,Gd2d4] [%clk 0:10:04] } 2... e6 { preparing d5 and letting queen and bishop into the game. } { [%cal Gd7d5] [%clk 0:10:04] } 3. c3 { strengthening the control over d4 square. fight for center. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc2c3,Gc3d4,Gd2d4,Gf3d4] [%clk 0:10:08] } 3... Nf6 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd7d5] [%clk 0:10:07] } 4. e5 { gaining space. } { [%clk 0:10:12] } 4... Nd5 { [%clk 0:10:11] } 5. Bc4 { kinda forcing knight back, if black does not want an ugly pawn structure. Although, once can argue that after an exchange on d5, black can go d6 and fix the structure back. } { [%clk 0:10:02] } 5... Nb6 { [%clk 0:10:14] } 6. Bb3 { [%clk 0:10:02] } 6... d6 { White has a better grip of center and more space. So logically black tries to break whites control. } { [%clk 0:10:10] } 7. d4 { protecting the control of the center back. } { [%clk 0:10:00] } 7... cxd4 { [%clk 0:08:41] } 8. cxd4 { [%clk 0:10:04] } 8... dxe5 { [%clk 0:08:46] } 9. Nxe5 { Quick eval after exchanges. White has an isolated pawn in the center but has a space advantage, which means pieces will be able to move freely and activity. Black also has to come up with a way to develop c8 Bishop. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc8] [%clk 0:10:08] } 9... Nc6?! { Im not really fond of this move to be honest. With this move, black basically says, after the exchange on c6, i ll probably have a time to push c5 if needed or at least white will have a d4 weakness in return, so that c6 weakness pawn wont matter much. Also black wants to develop his bishop via a6. } { [%clk 0:08:35] } 10. Nxc6 { [%clk 0:10:06] } 10... bxc6 { The way game has developed later, shows that this exchange on c6 was actually a critical point that give a certain direction to the game. It will become much more clear after 15 more moves, the role of this weakness. Judging by the story of the whole game, White kinda set his game plan mainly based on two things: c6 weakness and the weakened c5 square in the absence of b and d pawns. } { [%csl Gc6,Gd4] [%clk 0:08:40] } 11. O-O { I believe c5 was here necessary instead of Be7. Otherwise, as it turned out in the game, c6 pawn and c5 square became a pain in the butt. } { [%csl Gc6,Gd4][%cal Gc6c5] [%clk 0:10:10] } 11... Be7 { [%clk 0:08:37] } 12. Nc3 { [%clk 0:10:14] } 12... O-O { [%clk 0:08:30] } 13. Qf3 { White is switching to kingside for a while. Here Black is given a choice to exchange d4 pawn for c6. But this would give too much initiative and active play to white. After Qd4 Qc6 Rb8 Be3 Blacks pieces will start to go to awkward places. Hard to find a good square for blacks queen without being in the way of his other pieces. } { [%clk 0:09:36] } 13... Ba6 { [%clk 0:07:41] } 14. Rd1 { Notice how white develops his pieces. It all looks so simple and logical yet effective. } { [%clk 0:09:30] } 14... Nd5 { [%clk 0:07:45] } 15. Ne4 { Centralising the knight from where it can land on c5 or jump to kingside to create problems. } { [%csl Gc5,Gg5] [%clk 0:09:33] } 15... Qb6 { [%clk 0:06:55] } 16. Qg3 { White focuses on kingside while blacks pieces are currently far away from his king (Ba6,Qb6..) } { [%csl Gg3,Gg8,Gb6,Ga6,Ga8,Ge4][%cal Gc1h6,Gb3c2,Gc2h7] [%clk 0:09:32] } 16... Qb8 { [%clk 0:06:19] } 17. Bg5! { I kinda like this move. White wants to exchange dark squared bishops, so that the knight on c5 wont be able attacked by the bishop. Black has to do something as white has a superficial threat of taking on knight, which defends e7 bishop and winning a pawn after Bd5 Bg5 Bc6. } { [%csl Gg5,Gc5,Ge7,Ge4] [%clk 0:09:01] } 17... f6?! { Now, white has achieved something with his play on the kingside starting with Qf3; a new weakness on e6. } { [%csl Ge6,Gc6][%cal Gb3g8] [%clk 0:05:42] } 18. Bd2 { White can focus on his play in the center and queenside more. } { [%clk 0:09:01] } 18... Qxg3 { [%clk 0:05:45] } 19. hxg3 { Another thing black has to consider is where the light square bishop belongs. Weirdly, despite it looks like controlling the empty a6-f1 diagonal, it does not create any real threat neither can restrict whites rooks etc as they ll go to e1 c1. Even if u put the bishop on g6 or f5 and let him control g6-b1 diagonal, weirdly it is same! Does not really do much there either. So even though it looks like blacks most active piece, it actually has a malfunction. } { [%csl Ga6] [%clk 0:09:05] } 19... Bd3 { [%clk 0:05:43] } 20. Nc3 { [%clk 0:09:05] } 20... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:05:15] } 21. Rac1 { [%clk 0:09:06] } 21... Kf7 { Black is in defensive mode already. } { [%csl Gc6,Ge6,Gc8][%cal Gc8c6,Gf7e6] [%clk 0:05:16] } 22. Na4 { Next step for white is to control c5 square. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd3,Ge6][%cal Ga4c5] [%clk 0:08:45] } 22... Bb5 { We can feel the malfunction of light square bishop now even more. Where ever it goes, it feels random and awkwardly places. } { [%clk 0:05:19] } 23. Nc5 { [%clk 0:08:33] } 23... Bxc5 { [%clk 0:05:13] } 24. Rxc5 { [%clk 0:08:36] } 24... Nb6 { [%clk 0:05:16] } 25. Re1 { Attacking e6 to force him play Re6, which leaves c6 defended only by bishop. Nd5 here allows white a4. So we can already feel the shakiness of blacks position. } { [%csl Ge6] [%clk 0:08:18] } 25... Re8 { [%clk 0:05:20] } 26. Ra1! { Exploiting the bad placement of bishop. Blacks defend will soon crack under pressure. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ga2a4] [%clk 0:07:46] } 26... Red8 { [%clk 0:02:05] } 27. a4 { [%clk 0:07:19] } 27... Bc4 { A tactical miss that lets white finish the game quickly. } { [%clk 0:01:58] } 28. Bxc4 { [%clk 0:06:53] } 28... Rxd4 { [%clk 0:02:02] } 29. a5 { [%clk 0:06:38] } 29... Rxc4 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 30. axb6 { Black resigned here in the view of: } { [%clk 0:06:33] } 30... Rxc5 31. Rxa7+ Rxa7 32. bxa7 { [%cal Ga7a8,Gc5a5,Gd2a5] } 1-0


