1. f3 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 1... Nab6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 2. g3 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 2... h5 { i find h5 h4 or a5 a4 when queen is in the corner relies on similar principle like d4: opening space for queen with the difference that d4 primarily aims to attack center but also has a secondary advantage of opening queen. In 960, queens often get stuck later on. } { [%clk 0:04:59] } 3. f4 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 3... h4 { [%csl Gh3,Gh1][%cal Gh4h3] [%clk 0:04:56] } 4. g4 { [%csl Gh4,Gh8,Gh1] [%clk 0:02:26] } 4... h3 { [%csl Gh4] [%clk 0:04:55] } 5. Bf2 { [%clk 0:02:24] } 5... f6 { [%csl Gg8] [%clk 0:04:53] } 6. e4 { [%clk 0:02:21] } 6... e5 { [%clk 0:04:47] } 7. f5 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 7... d5 { attacking center. } { [%csl Gd4,Gf2][%cal Gd5d4,Gg8a2] [%clk 0:04:45] } 8. Bf3 { [%clk 0:02:10] } 8... d4 { killing both of the bishops. } { [%csl Gf3,Gf2,Ge5,Gd4,Gg8,Gh1] [%clk 0:04:45] } 9. d3 { [%clk 0:02:08] } 9... Nd6 { [%clk 0:04:43] } 10. Nab3 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 10... Be7 { [%clk 0:04:37] } 11. Ne2 { Generally when center is closed, usually sides attack on different flanks, where they are stronger. The specific formation of pawn chain usually determines which side should focus on which.
Think of a Kings Indian structure where white has c4-d5-e4 while black d6-e5. Due to d5 pawn, it means white is dominating on queenside, so typically white launches an attack on queenside whereas black tries to give a mate on the kingside.
Here black has d4-e5, so with same logic: black will play on queenside and white should try to play on kingside. But the problem is it is very hard to create an attack for white h3-Qh8 makes it too solid for black. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Gc5c4] [%clk 0:02:06] } 11... a5 { [%clk 0:04:33] } 12. Qg1 { [%clk 0:01:55] } 12... a4 { [%clk 0:04:30] } 13. Nbc1 { [%clk 0:01:54] } 13... c5 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc5c4] [%clk 0:04:23] } 14. a3 { [%clk 0:01:53] } 14... Qh6 { [%csl Gd2,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5,Gc1] [%clk 0:04:13] } 15. c3 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 15... Bb3 { [%cal Gb3c2,Gc5c4] [%clk 0:03:53] } 16. Nxb3 { [%clk 0:01:45] } 16... axb3 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 17. cxd4 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 17... cxd4 { [%csl Gc2,Gd2,Ga4,Gb2][%cal Gb6a4,Gb8c8,Gc8c2] [%clk 0:03:50] } 18. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:01:42] } 18... exd4 { [%clk 0:03:49] } 19. Bxd4 { [%clk 0:01:42] } 19... Nd7 { [%clk 0:03:29] } 20. Be3 { [%clk 0:01:40] } 20... Qh4+ { [%clk 0:03:27] } 21. Qg3 { [%clk 0:01:37] } 21... Qxg3+ { [%clk 0:03:23] } 22. hxg3 { [%clk 0:01:37] } 22... Ne5 { [%clk 0:03:23] } 23. Be2 { [%clk 0:01:36] } 23... Rc8 { [%csl Gd3,Gg4] [%clk 0:03:11] } 24. Rc1 { [%clk 0:01:27] } 24... Kd7 { [%clk 0:03:10] } 25. Kd2 { [%clk 0:01:22] } 25... h2 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 26. Rxc8 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 26... Rxc8 { [%clk 0:02:56] } 27. Bd1 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 27... Rh8 { [%csl Gh1][%cal Gh2h1] [%clk 0:02:51] } 28. Rh1 { [%clk 0:01:19] } 28... Kc6 { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gd1b3,Gd1g4] [%clk 0:02:29] } 29. g5 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 29... fxg5 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 30. g4 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 30... Rh3 { [%clk 0:02:12] } 31. Be2 { [%csl Ge7] [%clk 0:01:08] } 31... Bd8 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd8a5] [%clk 0:01:51] } 32. Bf1 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 32... Ba5+ { [%clk 0:01:49] } 33. Ke2 { [%clk 0:01:05] } 33... Rh8 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 34. Bxg5 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 34... Nxg4 { [%clk 0:01:40] } 35. Bf4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 35... Nb5 { [%csl Gd4,Ga3,Gb2][%cal Gb5a3,Gb3b1] [%clk 0:01:34] } 36. Kf3 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 36... Nf6 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 37. Rxh2 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 37... Rxh2 { [%clk 0:01: