1. b3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... e5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. c4 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb1c3,Ge2e3,Gd2d4] [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3. g3 { aiming for the control of d5. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g2,Gc4d5,Gb1c3] [%clk 0:03:00] } 3... Bc5 { does the bishop really belong that diagonal? it would be better to put it on g7 to neutralise a1 bishop. } { [%cal Ga7g1,Ga1h8] [%clk 0:02:57] } (3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7) 4. Bg2 { White is aiming for the control of d5 square. It is even more important to control it while bishop is on c5, because, black cannot play d5, but will probably play d6, after which the bishop is bit stuck there. White can easily neutralise c5 bishop with e3. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge3][%cal Ge2e3] [%clk 0:03:01] } 4... O-O { [%clk 0:02:56] } 5. O-O { [%clk 0:03:02] } 5... N8e7 { [%cal Gd7d5] [%clk 0:02:49] } 6. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5] [%clk 0:03:00] } 6... d6 { [%clk 0:02:45] } 7. e3 { [%csl Gc5,Ge3,Gd6,Gc7,Ge5,Ga7] [%clk 0:02:56] } 7... f5 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 8. Nd5 { [%cal Gd2d4] [%clk 0:02:44] } 8... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 9. Bxd5+ { [%clk 0:02:27] } 9... Kh8 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 10. d4 { [%clk 0:02:17] } 10... Bb4 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 11. Re2 { black is having hard time to find squares for his bishops. } { [%csl Gb4,Ga8] [%clk 0:02:15] } 11... Ba5 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 12. a3 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 12... Bb6 { [%clk 0:01:35] } 13. b4 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc4c5] [%clk 0:02:04] } 13... exd4 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 14. exd4 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc4c5] [%clk 0:02:00] } 14... a6 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 15. c5 { [%clk 0:01:45] } 15... Ba7 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 16. Bxc6 { [%clk 0:01:27] } 16... bxc6 { this was the whites concept of his play so far. White strategy was based completely on making these bishops out of play. While a8 bishop can get into game via b7-c8, bishop on a7 is permanently stuck. From now on, white has clear cut plan: trade all heave pieces and play a minor piece ending with piece up! } { [%csl Ga7,Ga8,Gc5,Gb4,Ga3,Gd4] [%clk 0:01:30] } 17. Rfe1 { [%clk 0:01:22] } 17... Bb7 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 18. Nd3 { [%clk 0:01:13] } 18... Bc8 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 19. Nf4 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 19... Bd7 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 20. Rxe8 { [%clk 0:01:08] } 20... Rxe8 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 21. Rxe8+ { [%clk 0:01:01] } 21... Qxe8 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 22. Qe2 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 22... Qxe2 { [%clk 0:01:18] } 23. Nxe2 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 23... Kg8 { White should keep the queenside structure as it is and now use his "material" advantage on kingside by bringing king and minors. } { [%clk 0:01:14] } 24. Kg2 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 24... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 25. h4 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 25... g6 { [%clk 0:01:12] } 26. Bc3 { [%csl Gh6,Gg5,Gf4][%cal Gg2f3,Gf3f4,Gf4g5,Gg5h6] [%clk 0:01:01] } 26... a5 { white does not need to do anything on queenside. } { [%clk 0:01:03] } 27. Kf3 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 27... axb4 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 28. axb4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 28... Be6 { [%clk 0:01:03] } 29. Nf4 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 29... Bb3 { [%clk 0:01:03] } 30. Nh3 { [%clk 0:00:48] } 30... h6 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 31. Bd2 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 31... h5 { How to place pieces optimally now? Bishop on h6 to control g7, King on g5 to control f6 and attack g6 pawn, Knight on f4 to attack g6. Notice white play revolves around on dark squares, which is unopposed due to blacks dark square bishop being out of play. } { [%csl Gf4,Gg5,Gh6,Gg7,Gf6] [%clk 0:00:57] } 32. Bh6 { [%clk 0:00:32] } 32... Bd1+ { [%clk 0:00:54] } 33. Kf4 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 33... Bb3 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 34. Kg5 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 34... Ke6 { [%clk 0:00:42] } 35. Nf4+ { 1-0 Black resigns. } { King can never cross the side and further material loss is inevitable. } { [%csl Ge6,Gd5,Ge5,Ga7] [%clk 0:00:31] } 1-0


