1. e4 { Notes by Dr. Tarrasch } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 (3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 (4... d6 5. d4 b5 6. Bb3 Nxd4 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4 { [%csl Gf6] } 8... c6 (8... c5 9. Qd5 { [%csl Ga8,Gf7] } 9... Be6 10. Qc6+ Bd7 11. Qd5 { [%cal Gd8a8,Gd5f7] } 11... c4 { [%csl Gd5] }))) 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 6. Qe2 (6. d5 Nb8 { Anderssen-Steinitz 1862 }) 6... Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 d5 { [%csl Gc7,Gc6,Gd5] } 11. exd6 { This gives away White's opening advantage by
consolidating the opponent's game. 11 Nbd2 was indicated. } 11... cxd6 12. Nbd2 Re8 { ! The R here threatens the White Q, and it
is interesting to see how quickly that indirect menace gives
Black some decisive advantage. } { [%csl Ge7] } 13. Rfe1 Bd7 14. Ne4 { This turns
out to be ineffective. It would have been relatively best to
retreat the Q to f1, the only if modest place where she could
enjoy a little peace. } 14... d5 { [%cal Ge8e1] } 15. Ned2 { The Kt mustn't go to g3,
since Bb4 would cost the exchange. } 15... Ba3 16. Be5 f6 17. Qa6 { White just manages to avoid the loss of a piece. } 17... fxe5 18. Qxa3 e4 19. Nd4 Qf6 20. c3 Rf8 { [%csl Gf2,Gd2] } 21. f3 Qg5 { One blow after
another Lasker plays with great strength. } { [%cal Gd7h3] } 22. Qc1 { [%cal Gb7c5,Gc5d3] } (22. Nf1 exf3 23. Nxf3 Rxf3) 22... Nc5 23. Nf1 Qg6 { [%csl Gd3] } 24. Re3 Nd3 25. Qd1 Nf4 26. Ng3 h5 27. Nde2 Nxg2 { ! Forcing
the issue with an elegant combination. } 28. Kxg2 exf3+ 29. Rxf3 Bh3+ 30. Kxh3 Qg4+ 31. Kg2 Qxf3+ 32. Kg1 h4 33. Nh1 Qe3+ { Resigns,
since Kg2 is punished by the pretty mate ...h3. } 34. Kg2 h3# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } 0-1


