ook got some activity. } { [%csl Gc2,Ge1,Ga1,Gd4,Ga7][%cal Ga1a7] [%clk 0:01:11] } 19... Nc2 { [%clk 0:01:41] } 20. Rd1 { [%clk 0:01:08] } 20... Nxe1 { [%clk 0:01:34] } 21. Rxe1 { white has two double pawns. black has a bishop in an open game. } { [%csl Gd8,Gh4,Gg3,Gc3,Gb2,Gb3,Gd4,Gd7] [%clk 0:01:11] } 21... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 22. Nb5 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 22... Be7 { black gives white to choice for an exchanging rook for minors, but black relies on whites weak pawn structure and solid pawn chain on kingsie (f-g-h pawns). } { [%csl Gf5,Gh5,Gg6,Gd4,Gb3,Gb2][%cal Ge1e7,Gh2h4,Gg7g6] [%clk 0:00:30] } 23. Rxe7+ { [%clk 0:00:31] } 23... Kxe7 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 24. Rxh4 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 24... g6 { black has a clear cut plan of going after d pawns then slowly advancing pawns on kingside. but knights are tricky so it wont be easy. white has to lose some tempos to bring rook into game (via h1-e1) as e4 and g4 is not available. this might be another hidden factor why black decided to give two minors for a rook. the time factor. he will use it to advance pawns. but two knights have to much mobility in long term, it is practically impossible to avoid forks. } { [%csl Gg4,Ge4,Gg3][%cal Gh4g4,Ge7d7,Gd7d4] [%clk 0:00:38] } 25. Kf2 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 25... Kxd7 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 26. Rh1 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 26... h4 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 27. Ne2 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 27... g5 { [%csl Gf4,Gg3] [%clk 0:00:33] } 28. d5 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 28... a6 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 29. Nbd4 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 29... Kd6 { still fairly balanced. but in long term two knights should be much easier to play and always some fork chances. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd4f5,Gd6d5] } 30. Nc3 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 30... Rhf8 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 31. Re1 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 31... Rf6 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 32. Nf3 Rg8 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 33. Ra1 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 33... a5 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 34. Nd2 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 34... g4 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 35. Nc4+ { [%clk 0:00:13] } 35... Kc5 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 36. d6 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 36... b5 3