{ Starting position with all bishops in the corner. As we ll see in the games, typically white aims to get a closed center with a one of the central pawn advanced to the 5th rank. With such pawn chain, (d5-e4 or d4-e5) white gets a space advantage and also make one of blacks bishop hit against a wall. } { [%csl Ga1,Gh1,Ga8,Gh8] }
1. e4 { especially if white can get to e5, it can create problems for knights development. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf6,Gd6,Gc8,Gg8][%cal Ge4e5,Gb2b3,Gd2d4,Gf2f4] } (1. b3 { 1.b3 is also logical, more than 1.g3. Because bishops on h8/h1 are undefended, which means if the b pawn is pushed, opponent cannot play immediately with g pawn as it will hang the bishop. And since, lets say after 1.b3 black cannot reply with 1...g6, white already has an edge in the race of controlling dark squares of the center (d4-e5) } { [%csl Gh8,Ge5,Gd4][%cal Ga1h8] }) *


