1. b3 { [%clk 0:15:08] } 1... b6 { [%clk 0:14:26] } 2. e4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge4e5] [%clk 0:14:27] } 2... e5 { unlike Adams, Donchenko does not want to allow white play e4. } { [%clk 0:14:03] } 3. Nd3 { attacks e5, but more importantly, by forcing black to defend, for example with d6, blacks pieces will start to find difficulties to develop freely without being in the way of each other. } { [%csl Ge5] [%clk 0:12:57] } 3... d6 { now, c8 knight can only go to e7, which means other knight can only go to f6 or h6. if it goes f6, it will block f8 rook and h8 bishop so only after f5 black can play f6. so logically knight will go to h6. } { [%csl Gc8,Gd6,Gb6,Ga7,Ge7,Gh6][%cal Gc8e7,Gg8h6] [%clk 0:12:30] } 4. O-O-O { [%csl Gd8,Gd4][%cal Gd1d8,Gf2f4,Gd2d4] [%clk 0:11:45] } 4... f5? { [%clk 0:10:00] } (4... g5 { would probably give black better fighting chances. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gc8e7,Gh7h6,Gf7f5,Gd8b8] }) 5. exf5 { [%clk 0:11:24] } 5... Nce7 { [%clk 0:10:01] } 6. f4 { [%clk 0:11:06] } 6... e4 { [%clk 0:08:52] } 7. Nf2 { [%clk 0:11:09] } 7... Nxf5 { [%clk 0:06:22] } 8. g4 { white has a development edge and blacks position have started to collapse so quickly. how did this happen, where did he go wrong? probably early 4...f5, opening board did not favour black. instead he could play maybe 4...g5, stopping f4 for the moment then Nce7 0-0-0 f5 etc. } { [%csl Gh1,Ge4,Ga1] [%clk 0:11:12] } 8... Nfh6 { [%clk 0:06:26] } 9. Ngh3 { [%csl Gf4,Gf8,Gh3] [%clk 0:08:33] } 9... d5 { [%clk 0:06:04] } 10. f5 { black cannot play even g6 due to pin. e6 is great square for the knight now. also blacks pawn in the center are more of a liability than an asset, as white can target with d3 at the right time. cuz now, d3 would lose to e3 and e2. } { [%csl Gf4,Ge6,Gh8][%cal Gh3f4,Gf4e6,Ga1h8] [%clk 0:08:21] } 10... O-O-O { [%clk 0:05:37] } 11. Ng5 { [%csl Ge6,Gh7,Gf8] [%clk 0:08:15] } 11... Rf6 { [%clk 0:03:25] } 12. Nxh7 { [%clk 0:07:25] } 12... Rc6 { [%clk 0:03:23] } 13. Ng5 { [%clk 0:07:19] } 13... Qe7 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 14. Ne6 { blacks pieces are placed super awkwardly, without any harmony. only after 14 moves! } { [%csl Gc6,Ga8,Gg8,Gh8,Gh6] [%clk 0:07:17] } 14... Qa3+ { a desparate check which brings nothing as queen alone cannot create any danger when there is Bb2. Fianchetto bishops are really good defender. } { [%clk 0:02:46] } 15. Bb2 { [%clk 0:05:12] } 15... Qxa2 { [%csl Gb3,Gc1][%cal Ga2b3,Gc6c1] [%clk 0:02:45] } 16. Nxd8 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Ga2b3,Gd8c6] [%clk 0:05:12] } 16... Kxd8 { [%clk 0:02:11] } 17. Nxe4 { making use of the clumsy placement of pieces. } { [%csl Gc6,Ga8][%cal Gd5e4,Gh1e4,Ge1e4] [%clk 0:04:38] } 17... dxe4 { [%clk 0:01:36] } (17... Qxb3 18. Nc3 { [%csl Gb3,Gd5][%cal Gc2b3,Gh1d5] }) 18. Qxe4 { [%clk 0:04:14] } (18. Bxe4) 18... Nf6 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 19. Qb4 { [%csl Gf8,Gc6,Gb3][%cal Gb4f8,Gh1c6] [%clk 0:03:57] } 19... Nd7 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 20. Bxc6 { [%clk 0:02:44] } 20... Bxc6 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 21. Qc4 { [%csl Gf7,Gg8,Gh6,Ga2][%cal Gg4g5,Gc4g8] [%clk 0:02:46] } 21... Bg2 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 22. g5 { [%clk 0:02:32] } 22... Bxf1 23. Rxf1 { [%clk 0:02:33] } 23... b5 24. Qe6 { [%csl Gg8] [%clk 0:02:01] } 24... Ng4 25. Qg8+ { [%clk 0:01:55] } 25... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 26. Qxh8 { while in keymer - adams game, 2..f5 determined the whole story of the game, here 4...f5 played that role. Interestingly in this round, starting with all bishops in the corner, white has won convincingly. It shows black needs to be very careful in the first couple of moves as it can quickly result in a pawn structure in whites favor. So black has to come up with a sound plan to not to allow white gaining space in closed center and killing one of fianchetto bishops. but meantime, he also has to make sure he has enough space to develop his pieces harmoniously. looks like a difficult task and starting position for black. } { [%clk 0:01:49] } 1-0


