{ f4-g3-Nf3 set up suggests itself. But the main question this position offers is where does the e1 bishop belong? It is always a central question to answer in 960, when bishop starts in the center, because it generally requires some unusual pawn pushes and whole development process gets effected by that pawn structure. As we have seen in the games, c3 square looks a like a good place for e1 bishop. There, it neutralises blacks h8 bishop and puts pressure on dark squares of the center. } { [%csl Ge1,Gc3][%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g3,Gg1f3,Gd2d3,Gc2c4,Ge1c3] }
1. f4 Nf6 2. g3 Ng8 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d3 Ng8 5. c4 Nf6 6. Bc3 { some set up for white to look for and ideas to play on the center depending on how black develops. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd1f2,Ge2e4] } *


