1. f4 { [%clk 0:15:07] } 1... d5 { [%csl Ge5] [%clk 0:14:47] } 2. g3 { the usual english type of set up in 960. often when rook is on c or f next to knight and bishop, c4 b3 nc3 or f4 nf3 g3 is a typical set up. } { [%csl Gf4,Gf1,Gh1,Gg3][%cal Gg1f3] [%clk 0:14:52] } 2... Nf6 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gg1f3,Gf3e5] [%clk 0:14:22] } 3. d3 { neither c3 nor e3 makes any sense, d4 weakens e4. so only d3 makes sense to develop bishop on e1. also d3 prepares e4 later for white when the d1 knight comes to support. } { [%csl Ge4,Ge1,Gd1][%cal Gd1f2,Ge1c3,Ge2e4] [%clk 0:14:24] } 3... g6 { [%csl Gh8] [%clk 0:13:41] } 4. Bc3 { establishing more control over dark squares of center. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gh8] [%clk 0:13:53] } 4... Bc6 { [%clk 0:11:46] } 5. Nf3 { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gg5] [%clk 0:12:36] } 5... b6 { [%clk 0:11:49] } 6. Nf2 { [%cal Ge2e4,Gc1e1] [%clk 0:11:56] } 6... Bb7 { [%clk 0:11:22] } 7. Qe1 { white is fighting for center. } { [%cal Ge2e4] [%clk 0:11:33] } 7... Nc6 { [%clk 0:10:35] } 8. e4 { [%clk 0:09:56] } 8... Qd7 { [%clk 0:08:44] } 9. Ne5? { to me, this Ne5 move only makes sense if it can be followed by fxe5-d4. with Nxe5 Bxe5 white does not achieve much by the exchange and simplification. } { [%clk 0:06:12] } (9. O-O-O { natural. } 9... d4 { is not a big deal as it cannot be followed with e5 easily. } 10. Bd2) (9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Bxh8 Rxh8 11. O-O-O O-O-O { suggested by engine but is less natural as black pieces have activity and free space. so i would not prefer exd5 exchanges. white needs to keep the tension. }) 9... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:08:19] } 10. Bxe5 { [%clk 0:05:57] } (10. fxe5 Ng4 (10... Ne8 11. d4 { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gh8] }) (10... d4 { is a problem so 10.fxe5 does is not desirable. therefore i find 9.Ne5 premature. }) 11. Nxg4 Qxg4) 10... O-O-O { [%clk 0:06:58] } 11. a4 { [%clk 0:03:56] } 11... dxe4 { [%clk 0:05:50] } 12. dxe4 { black has the d file now and no real problems.. White had an early advantage in the center but he did not make any real progress, instead simplified it with some trades. Now bishop on e5 in front of pawns stands a bit awkward, so blocking e4, which then blocks bishop on h1 and knight on f2. } { [%csl Gd7,Gd8,Ge5,Gf4,Gf2,Gh1,Ge4] [%clk 0:03:53] } 12... Qd2 { [%clk 0:04:37] } 13. Bc3 { [%clk 0:03:30] } 13... Qxe1+ { [%clk 0:04:25] } 14. Rxe1 { [%clk 0:03:32] } 14... a5 { [%clk 0:04:23] } 15. Ra3 { [%clk 0:01:57] } 15... Nd7 { [%clk 0:03:31] } 16. e5 { tries to kill the bishop on h8. but without not many pieces left, whites pawn chain can be easily challenged with f6-g5 ideas. } { [%csl Gh8,Ge5,Gf4] [%clk 0:01:42] } 16... Bxh1 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 17. Rxh1 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 17... f6 { knight on f2 has not good squares, whether on e4 or on d3, it is restricted by pawns and doesnt do anything on these squares. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf2][%cal Gf8f2] [%clk 0:02:39] } 18. Nd3 { rook on a3 now looks silly. } { [%csl Gc3,Ga3,Gd3] [%clk 0:01:23] } 18... fxe5 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 19. fxe5 { black is slowly getting control. controlling open file and also have a real target on e5. whereas whites pieces lack coordination. } { [%csl Gf8,Ge5] [%clk 0:01:26] } 19... Rf5 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd8f8] [%clk 0:02:23] } 20. Re1 { [%clk 0:01:08] } 20... Rdf8 { [%clk 0:02:19] } 21. e6 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 21... Nf6 { [%csl Gd5] [%clk 0:01:50] } 22. b4 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 22... Nd5 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 23. Bxh8 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 23... axb4 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 24. Nxb4 { [%clk 0:00:15] } (24. Rb3 Rxh8 25. Nxb4 Nxb4 26. Rxb4 Rd8 { black is playing for two results. } { [%csl Gd8,Gf5][%cal Gd8d2,Gf5f2] }) 24... Nxb4 { soon e6 will fall and black will penetrate to 2nd rank and attack c2/h2. } { [%csl Ga4,Gc2,Ge6,Gh2][%cal Gf5f2] [%clk 0:00:59] } 25. Bg7 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 25... Rf1 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 26. Bxf8 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 26... Rxe1+ { [%clk 0:00:47] } 27. Kb2 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 27... Rxe6 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 28. Rb3 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 28... Nc6 { [%clk 0:00:37] } 29. Bg7 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 29... Re2 { [%clk 0:00:35] } 30. h4 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 30... e5 { now blacks plan is easy, simply push em baby. and should have no technical problems converting it. } { [%cal Ge5e1] [%clk 0:00:36] } 31. Rd3 h5 { fixing first. } { [%csl Gg3,Gh4] [%clk 0:00:27] } 32. Rc3 Kb7 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 33. Kc1 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 33... Re4 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ge4g4] [%clk 0:00:27] } 34. Ra3 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 34... Na5 { [%csl Gc4,Ge1][%cal Ga5c4,Ge4e1] [%clk 0:00:24] } 35. Rf3 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 35... Nc4 { [%csl Ge1] [%clk 0:00:23] } 36. Kd1 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 36... Ne3+ { [%clk 0:00:24] } 37. Kd2 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 37... Nf5 { [%csl Gg3,Gg7] [%clk 0:00:28] } 38. Bh8 { [%clk 0:00:20] } 38... Rd4+ { [%clk 0:00:27] } 39. Rd3 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 39... Re4 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 40. c3 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 40... Kc6 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 41. Bf6 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 41... Nd6 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 42. Kc2 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 42... Kd7 { [%cal Gd7e6,Ge6f5,Gf5g4] [%clk 0:00:29] } 43. Kb3 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 43... Re2 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 44. Rd1 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 44... Kc6 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 45. Bg5 Ne4 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 46. Bd8 Nc5+ { [%clk 0:00:33] } 47. Ka3 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 47... Re3 { [%csl Gc3,Gg3] [%clk 0:00:33] } 48. Kb4 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 48... Re4+ { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gb4a3,Ge4a4] [%clk 0:00:31] } 49. c4 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 49... Re3 { mate is now unavoidable. story of the game: white had an early control in the center, instead of keeping the tension, ask black questions for his development etc. White acted prematurely with 1.Ne5 and simplified too much. That was the turning point of the game. In a simplified position e5-f4 served in blacks favor as targets. Blacks pieces got activity, while white struggled to coordinate his pieces (Rook on a3, Knight on f2). As a result white collapsed and lost e pawn which left black with an easy winning endgame. } { [%csl Gb3,Gb4][%cal Ge3b3] [%clk 0:00:35] } 50. Rb1 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 50... Na6# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:00:38] } 0-1


