,Gh7f5,Gf7f5] [%clk 0:01:17] } 20... e4 { i m not a big fan of this move unless there is a concrete reason behind it. not only it closes the diagonal for h7 bishop but enables white to coordinate his pieces bit more with the free square d4. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4] [%clk 0:00:31] } 21. cxd5 { [%clk 0:00:49] } 21... cxd5 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 22. N3d4 { [%csl Ge5,Ga8,Gb8,Gb1][%cal Gc7e5,Ga8b8] [%clk 0:00:49] } 22... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:00:19] } (22... Bxf5 { black can now exchange his bishop for the knight as it is not doing much on the diagonal anymore. Also after Nf5, white wont have connected knights and it will be hard to close the diagonal for Bishop on e5 without pawn sacrifice on d4. } 23. gxf5 (23. Nxf5 Be5 (23... f3 { not even allowing exf4 and closing kingside. } 24. Bf1 (24. Bd1) 24... Be5 { devastating attack for black. powerful bishop on e5. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc7][%cal Gd7b7,Gf7c7,Ga4a3] })) 23... Nxd4 24. exd4 { [%cal Gc7d6,Gd7f5,Gf7b7] }) 23. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 23... Ba5 { i believe bishop belongs to e5 rather than a5. } { [%clk 0:00:15] } (23... Be5 { [%csl Ge5] }) 24. Bb5 { [%clk 0:00:42] } 24... Qd6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 25. Rd1 { now white is solving his problems and getting space& activity. knight on d4 is strong, it would be better to keep the knight on e6 rather than to have bishop on h7 now. } { [%csl Gh7] [%clk 0:00:26] } 25... Rc7 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 26. Qxa4 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 26... Rcc8 { black cannot make any real good use of his minor pieces, which is the big issue. blocked by his own central pawns and the bishop on a5 is awkwardly places, no real good discoveries. so blacks attack is not as effective as it could be.. } { [%csl Ga5,Gh7,Gf6,Gd5,Ge4] } 27. Qb3 { [%csl Gd5] [%clk 0:00:26] } 27... fxe3 28. Bxe3 { white is now getting the control. solid center. target on d5. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge3,Gd5,Gb5] [%clk 0:00:22] } 28... Kh8 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 29. a4 { a typical defensive set up. also very common in some najdorf or sicilian games. } { [%csl Gb5,Ga4]