1. d4 { [%cal Ge1f3] } (1. f4 { does not work really as it can be attacked with c6, then either e3 blocks the bishop or g3 weakens light squares. for same reason c4 is not a good option. This means either d4 or e4 logical ways to start. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge1f3,Gc7c6,Gb8f4] } 1... c6 2. e3 { [%csl Gg1,Gf1] } (2. g3 { [%csl Gg2,Gf3,Gh3] })) (1. e4 { another way to develop. but one has to be careful after e4-d4 Ng3 for Bf4 checks. } { [%cal Gf1g3,Gf2f3,Gd2d4,Gc2c3] } 1... f6 2. Ng3 (2. d4 c6 3. f3 { important to get Be3 first then Ng3 otherwise some problems for white. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gg1e3] }) 2... c6 { [%csl Gd2,Gf4][%cal Gb8f4] } 3. d4 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gb8f4] } 3... Bf4+) 1... d5 2. c3 { [%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4,Gg1e3] } (2. Nf3 { is also possible but probably less promising. } { [%cal Gh2h3,Gg1h2] }) (2. f3 { [%cal Ge2e4] } 2... c6 3. e4 { white wants to play e5 next. } { [%cal Gb8f4,Gg1e3,Ge4e5] } 3... f6 (3... h6 4. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gb8,Ge8,Gf6,Gd6][%cal Gg8h7,Ga7a5,Gb8a7,Gc2c3] })) *


