{ f4-g3 suggests itself when bishops are in the right corner of the board. In almost all games except David Anton game, white seemed to struggle. Games have shown that white needs to be careful with aggressive moves such as c4 or b4. } { [%csl Gg1,Gh1][%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g3] }
1... f5 { c5 and e5 are key squares white will try to take control of. } { [%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Ga1b3,Ge1f3] } 2. c4 { an early c4 allows black to attack with b5 as we have seen in the Harikrishna game. So c4 should be better played when the knight on a8 is already developed and preferably supported with d3. } { [%csl Gc4,Ga8][%cal Gc7c6,Gb7b5,Gg7g6,Ge8f6,Gd2d3] } (2. b4 { [%csl Gc4,Ga4,Ga2][%cal Gc7c6] }) (2. g3 c6 { [%csl Gc6,Gd7,Gh1][%cal Ge7e5,Gd7d5,Gg7g6] } (2... g6 3. c3 { [%cal Ge2e4,Gd2d4,Ga1b3] })) (2. O-O-O { 0-0-0 is likely to happen at some point in the game as 0-0 requires too much work. in couple of games, king could not find his shelter and stayed on d1 for a while. This was due to c4 as c4 makes sense when rook is on c1 but not with 0-0-0 combined since there is also no knight on c3 but on b3. So combining 0-0-0 with c3 makes more sense to me. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc5][%cal Ga1b3,Gc2c3,Gd2d4,Ge1f3,Gg2g3] }) *


