enside (Qg2 battery) } { [%csl Gc6,Gb7,Gf8] [%clk 0:00:26] } 25... a6 (25... Rxd3 26. exd3 Qxd3+ 27. Ka1 Bxc4 { was maybe the only chance for black to hold. } { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gd3c2,Gc2a2] } 28. Bg2 Qc2 { [%csl Ga2] } 29. d3 { [%cal Gf2b2] } 29... Qc3+ 30. Qb2 Qxb2+ 31. Kxb2 Bxd3 { [%csl Gc5,Gb6,Ga7,Gd3,Gf1] } 32. Rxf6 Bxf1 33. Rxf8 Bxg2 34. Rf7+ Kc6) 26. Qg2 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 26... Qc8 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 27. Qg5 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 27... Qe6 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 28. Qg2 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 28... Qc8 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 29. R1f2 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 29... Rf7 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 30. Ne5 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 30... Rf8 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 31. d3 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 31... Kd8 32. Ng4 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 32... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 33. Nxf6 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 33... Rfxf6 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 34. Qg5 { [%cal Gg5e7] [%clk 0:00:15] } 34... Qf8 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 35. Bd5 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gg5e5,Gf4f6] [%clk 0:00:13] } 35... Bxd5 36. cxd5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Qe5 and winning rook is unavoidable now. Story of the game: It was a fighting game with lots of twists. Black had winning chances after whites g4. But he failed to attack the king in the middle of the board, missed Ne4. It was a critical moment, because this is usually how wins slip away with huge advantage: missing an accurate and immediate execution. You build up and build up your advantage to a point where it should be executed effectively, once missed that point, advantage starts to melt away quickly. Retreating Qb6 was a sign that tables can turn. Exactly at such moments, opponent jumps back into game.
Then he could still win slowly if he had played 19... or 20...h5 and hold onto material advantage. He chose instead an unsound attack to king, which was very slow. White managed to hold but also create two weaknesses in meantime and eventually converted. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gg5e5,Gf4f6] [%clk 0:00:16] } 1-0


