1. d4 { White ideally wants to build a strong center with 1.d4 Nc3-Bf4-f3-e4-0-0-0. So once white achieves e4, it gets quiet an easy play. Therefore black needs a better reply than 1...d5. } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gc1f4,Gf2f3] } (1. e4 e5 { does not make much sense as c3-d4 follow up is not as effective as 1.d4 followed by f3-e4. }) (1. f4 { an alternative way of developing ideal for white 1.f4-g3-Nf3. } { [%cal Gg2g3,Gg1f3,Gd2d3,Ge2e4,Gb1c3] }) 1... g6 { as we have seen Adams game, once white gets e4, it has an easy play. One difference from italian is that after the castle (here 0-0-0), the rook on d1 is immediately opposed to the king, which saves a tempo and makes attack even faster. (1.e4 e5 2. Nf3-Bc4 0-0 and Re1 is an extra move there) Therefore black has to be extra careful to deal with whites e4 and center attack in such starting position. 1...g6 suggests itself as a way of immediate reaction by targeting d4 and forcing white to defend and slow its plan down. } { [%csl Gd4,Gg6][%cal Gh8d4] } (1... d5 { as we have seen in the games, d5 reply causes black some problems after Nc3. } 2. Nc3 { not only attacks d5 but more importantly prepares e4 } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4] } 2... Nf6 3. f3 { would be premature. } (3. Bf4 { prevents e5 and puts pressure on c7 already. like bishop on c4 puts pressure on f7 in the italian. } { [%csl Ge5,Gc7][%cal Gf4e5,Gf2f3,Ge2e4] }) 3... e5) *


