1. d4 { [%clk 0:15:08] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:14:11] } 2. g3 { [%clk 0:14:53] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 0:13:37] } 3. Bg2 { [%clk 0:14:48] } 3... Nc6 { [%clk 0:13:20] } 4. Nf3 { [%clk 0:14:19] } 4... Bf5 { [%clk 0:12:21] } 5. Qc3 { [%clk 0:13:46] } 5... g6 { [%clk 0:11:03] } 6. O-O { Harikrishna wanted to achieve the familiar Nf3-g3-Bg2-0-0 set up as quickly as possible and for that he was even ready to put his queen on c3. But i believe aiming for this set up and even willingness to put queen on c3 was against the spirit of the position. As we see in other games, aiming for e4 after 1.d4 looks more promising and asks questions to black right from the start. The slow approach by white does not create any problem for black. } { [%csl Ge4] [%clk 0:12:15] } 6... O-O-O { [%csl Gb7,Ge4][%cal Ge7e5,Gc3b3,Ga2a6] [%clk 0:08:57] } 7. Bf4 { [%csl Gc7] [%clk 0:10:28] } 7... Ne4 { [%csl Gd4,Gc6,Gf3,Gh8][%cal Gc3b3] [%clk 0:08:44] } 8. Qe3 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gf8g8,Gg6g5] [%clk 0:09:15] } (8. Qb3 Nxd4 (8... Bxd4)) 8... f6 { [%cal Gg6g5] [%clk 0:06:57] } (8... Rg8 { [%cal Gg6g5] }) 9. c4 { white has Bc7 in mind, so he wants to open the c-file to create problems for black king on c7. } { [%cal Gf4c7,Gc4d5,Gf1c1] [%clk 0:08:33] } 9... g5 { [%clk 0:05:51] } 10. Bxc7 { [%clk 0:07:53] } 10... Kxc7 { [%clk 0:05:38] } 11. cxd5 { [%clk 0:07:56] } 11... Rxd5 { [%clk 0:05:01] } 12. Nfd2 { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2c6] [%clk 0:07:51] } 12... Nxd2 { [%clk 0:04:51] } 13. Nxd2 { [%clk 0:07:54] } 13... e6 { [%clk 0:04:12] } (13... Rd8 14. d5 { white has great compensation for the sac. }) 14. Qc3 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge2e4] [%clk 0:05:40] } (14. Bxd5 exd5 { bishop pair. } { [%csl Gf5,Gh8] }) 14... Bg6 { [%clk 0:03:32] } (14... Kb8 15. e4 Nxd4 16. Rfe1 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Rd7 { with promising position for black. } { [%csl Gh8][%cal Gf6f5,Ge6e5] }) 15. b4 { [%cal Gg2d5,Gb4b5] [%clk 0:05:28] } 15... Kb8 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 16. Nb3 { [%csl Gc5] [%clk 0:04:35] } 16... Ne7 { [%clk 0:01:27] } 17. Nc5 { [%clk 0:03:43] } 17... Qc8 { [%clk 0:00:38] } 18. Rac1 { [%clk 0:03:41] } 18... b6?? { [%clk 0:00:18] } (18... Be8 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Qe3) (18... Bf7) 19. Na6+ { [%clk 0:02:18] } 19... Qxa6 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 20. Qc7+ { [%clk 0:02:21] } 20... Ka8 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 21. Qxe7 { [%csl Gf8,Gd5][%cal Ge7e6,Gg2a8] [%clk 0:02:16] } 21... Re8 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 22. Qd7 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gg2d5] [%clk 0:01:29] } 22... f5 23. Bxd5+ { [%clk 0:01:09] } 23... exd5 24. b5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { White did not develop accordingly to the spirit of the nature and black had an early edge and control in the center. White struggled to find appropriate places for his pieces, as queen on c3/e3 was in the way of whites pieces. This has led to a kind of crisis, which white wanted to solve practically with a bishop sacrifice on c7. So, first black had initiative and as a result of it, it forced white to sacrifice on c7 and gained material. But after that it required precise play by black as white now had the initiative for the sacrificed material. Eventually as a result, black cracked under pressure. The story of a game is not a rare tragicomic story in chess. First one side has an advantage and it transforms after a while into material advantage which then results in active play or initiative for the side with less material. The side with material advantage then has to deal with pressure and defend accurately, but fails many times in this twisted chain of events which was initiated by himself. And therein lies the tragicomedy. He wants it, he gets it, but it turns out bad for him in the end.. } { [%cal Ga6b7,Gc1c7,Gd7c6] [%clk 0:01:12] } 1-0


