1. d4 { [%clk 0:15:09] } 1... d5 { [%clk 0:14:14] } 2. Nc3 { [%csl Gd5,Ge4] [%clk 0:14:37] } 2... Nf6 { [%clk 0:14:12] } 3. Bf4 { same logic as in italian opening, but just as if the board is reversed horizontally. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4,Gf4c7] [%clk 0:14:30] } 3... g6 { [%clk 0:12:19] } 4. O-O-O { [%clk 0:14:14] } 4... c6 { [%clk 0:11:09] } 5. f3 { as we have seen before, once white gets e4, it has an easy play. One difference from italian is that after castle, the rook is immediately opposed to the king, which saves a tempo and makes attack even faster. (1.e4 e5 2. Nf3-Bc4 0-0 and Re1 is an extra move there) Therefore black has to be extra careful to deal with whites e4 and center attack in such starting position. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge2e4] [%clk 0:13:46] } 5... Qd7 { [%clk 0:10:56] } 6. Bh6 { [%clk 0:13:15] } 6... Re8 { black cannot 0-0 anymore. } { [%clk 0:10:58] } 7. e4 { [%clk 0:13:07] } 7... Qc7 { [%clk 0:10:48] } 8. Nge2 { white has a very pleasant position to play, while black still has to solve development issues. } { [%csl Gd1,Gd8][%cal Gh6f4,Gg2g4,Ge4e5] [%clk 0:12:02] } 8... Na6 { [%clk 0:10:20] } 9. Bf4 { [%clk 0:10:17] } 9... Qa5 { [%clk 0:10:16] } 10. Kb1 { [%clk 0:09:09] } 10... Bd7 { [%clk 0:09:43] } 11. Nc1 { [%clk 0:06:55] } 11... O-O-O { [%clk 0:08:21] } 12. Nb3 { queen is getting short of squares. } { [%clk 0:06:47] } 12... Qb6 { [%clk 0:08:25] } 13. a3 { [%clk 0:05:31] } 13... Nh5 { [%clk 0:07:56] } 14. Be3 { [%clk 0:05:29] } 14... Nc7 { [%clk 0:06:54] } 15. g4 { [%clk 0:05:13] } 15... Ng7 { [%csl Gf5,Gh5,Gg7,Gh8] [%clk 0:06:47] } 16. Na4 { [%clk 0:04:32] } 16... Qb5 { [%clk 0:06:50] } 17. Nac5 { [%clk 0:03:59] } 17... Nge6 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 18. Rd3 { [%clk 0:03:28] } (18. a4 Qb6 19. Bd2 Nxc5 20. Ba5 Qa6 (20... Nxb3 21. Bxb6 axb6 22. cxb3 { [%csl Gb6,Gh7][%cal Ge4e5,Gf3f4,Gh2h3,Ge1b4,Ge1h4] }) 21. Nxc5 Qc4 22. b3) 18... Na6 { [%clk 0:04:18] } 19. a4 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 19... Qb6 { [%clk 0:04:21] } 20. exd5 { an unfortunate strategical decision. ed5 cd5 helps black as pieces get more room now. Bishop on d7 stands better than before. Also white has no more e5 option to shut h8 bishop down. In return white does not gain any advantage with these trades. } { [%clk 0:01:43] } 20... cxd5? { now bishop attack a4, after Kb8-Rc8 black will get a play on c file. also bishop on h8 puts pressure on d4. } { [%csl Ga4,Gd4][%cal Gd7a4,Gc8b8,Gd8c8,Gc8c1,Ge6c5,Gh8d4] [%clk 0:04:16] } 21. f4 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 21... Nexc5 { [%clk 0:03:42] } 22. dxc5 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 22... Qb4 { [%clk 0:03:39] } 23. Bd2 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 23... Qxa4 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gf1f4] [%clk 0:03:13] } 24. Rxd5 { [%clk 0:00:21] } (24. f5 { with the idea of Rf4 and not allowing Be6. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gf1f4] }) 24... Be6 { from a very cramped position, suddenly black found himself in an attacking position just in couple of moves starting with 20. exd5? } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Ge6b3,Gh8b2,Ga6b4] [%clk 0:02:51] } 25. Rxd8+ { [%clk 0:00:13] } 25... Rxd8 { blacks pieces are now standing perfectly. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd8,Ge6,Gh8,Ga4][%cal Ga6c5] [%clk 0:02:55] } 26. Rf3 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 26... Nxc5 { [%clk 0:02:40] } 27. f5 (27. Nc1 Ne4 { [%csl Gd2] }) 27... Nxb3 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 28. cxb3 Bxb3 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 29. Rxb3 Qxb3 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 30. Bc1 Qd3+ { [%clk 0:02:01] } (30... Rd1 { also. }) 31. Ka1 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 31... Rd6 { 0-1 White resigns. } { white had amazing position and blacks pieces were cramped. but white let his advantage melt with a series of exchanges in the center, which relieved blacks position and white found himself suddenly in the middle of an devastating attack. } { [%csl Ga6][%cal Gd6a6] [%clk 0:01:54] } 0-1


